,Recommended,226840,9747431,"Posted: 6 April, 2014",all,Minax,"The third part of a game franchise is often where things are starting to go downhill rapidly, especially if the franchise has been around for a long time (1999) and managed to establish something like a ""cult following"". The franchise left some big shoes to fill when they released Age of Wonders: Shadow Magic 11 years ago, and Age of Wonders 3 fills them admirably.At its core the Age of Wonders series are turn-based strategy games with turn-based strategic battles set in a fantasy world full of fantastic creatures and magic. You pick between different races, create your leader, build an empire and set out to claim the land as your own. You can forge alliances with other leaders (both AI or other players, if you play multiplayer matches) or try to conquer the world on your own. Your leader and hireable heroes are different to your main army in that they can level up and gain a plethora of new abilities and equippable items. Magic is an always-present factor in Age of Wonders. You constantly research new sorceries and in battle you will most often find yourself flinging powerful spells with your heroes while the rest of your army engages in more traditional combat, which also has its own nuances with line-of-sight penalties and flanking mechanics, on top of other things.Age of Wonders 3 stays true to the spirit of the previous titles while bringing new features to the table. The most game-changing feature is the introduction of classes. When you start a game you pick a leader, race, class and specialization. Each class gets many dedicated units that are restricted to this class only, for example Arch-druids can get hunters while Mages can summon wisps. The same is true for spells, a Warlord could get a spell that sends an enemy unit into a fit of rage, making it unable to tell friend from foe, while a Rogue might send a plague of brigands upon an enemy city.Here are some of the features you can expect:+ 6 playable races, all with their benefits and drawbacks (Draconian, Dwarves, High-Elves, Goblins, Humans, Orcs)+ Many different spells and units to research, depending on your chosen race, class and specialization+ Units can level up and gain increased stats, while heroes gain new abilities+ Neutral cities and dwellings that offer quests and access to unique units and items for your heroes+ 2 full campaigns serving as a tutorial+ Random map generator with a plethora of changeable settings to tailor maps to your liking+ 8 pre-built scenarios of varying sizes with their unique twists, for multiplayer as well as singleplayer+ Multiplayer with up to 8 players+ Ships with the same level editor the developers useIf you are into turn-based strategy games you owe it to yourself to at least take a closer look at Age of Wonders 3!"
,Recommended,226840,26313709,"Posted: 30 October, 2016",all,Overcast451,"Age of Wonders III is an excellent 4x Strategy Game. I first found this game when looking for a game similar to the late 90's game called ""Lords of Magic"". Lords of magic was quite similar to this game, but so much was done wrong in that game. The AI was just too simple, once you knew a couple tricks - you could beat it without thought.Not so for Age of Wonders, the AI is a good challenge, to me at least. There are a number of classes to pick from as well of a number of skill paths to tailor for your character that will change the play style for any class. The lore and immersion is fantastic, the help/information system is very in-depth and explains any game concept I've had a question about. One thing I really like about this game is the ability to create my own leaders for either the AI or myself and then customize who I'm up against or just let it pick randomly.The game seems pretty well balanced overall, although the Necromancer AI leaders can tend to get fairly powerful and be an incessant threat if they get far enough. Although, there are classes and skill paths that can take care of this easily - not every class/skill combination will do well against them. But this game offers a lot of custom settings when creating a new map, so you can just choose not play against AI classes that might be too tough for your level of play or make them all one class, if you so choose.This game runs good in a seamless window as well as full screen - so those with mutiple displays will not be disappointed. The mouse automatically constrains to the play area for easy scrolling around the map/battle field - and also handles switching to windows very easily. I don't think this game has ever crashed on me at all, it's stable and runs well.I have to also give praise to the music in this game. It's excellent. I love the soundtrack in this game. I play this frequently, and will buy more expansions in this series without hesitation. 10 out of 10!"
