76561198096248663,Recommended,226840,25155346,"Posted: 25 August, 2016",all,lucibuis,"I discovered this game about one year ago and never stopped playing it. I'm a big fan of strategy games and AOW 3 has really met and exceeded most of my expectations.I recommend to purchase the two expansions Golden Realms and Eternal Lords because they add a lot to the base game.Gameplay is a mix of Civilization and Might and Magic: you build and conquer cities and occupy resources to be able to field powerful armies and defeat your enemies.But what really shines through is the great variety of units, spells, maps, geographies and playstyles that make AOW3's replayability almost endless. There are 9 races, 7 classes and about 15 magic specializations that can be mixed and matched in endless combinations. The races play similar but have different strengths against each other.The classes play different, i.e. Archdruids summon animals, Horned Gods and build Hunters and Shamans and their armies are very fast, Dreadnoughts build machines of increasing power and are way slower. Then, an elven archdruid focuses on range and shock damage while a goblin archdruid focuses on blight damage and fast growth of their cities.Necromancers gain most of their armies from dead enemies, sorcerers and archdruids from summoning spells, warlords and theocrats from recruiting in cities, etc.Early game plays different from late game, and the random map generator allows the customization of every map feature.The graphics, art and storyline of the campaign are superb. The atmosphere of the game is unique, mysterious and magical.Game is easy to grasp but hard to master because of the miriads of combinations and customizations possible.Highly recommended5/5"
76561198027061200,Not Recommended,226840,9723530,"Posted: 4 April, 2014",all,Kaskarn,"I looked forward to this game for months, pre-ordered it and took the afternoon off to play it the day of release. I consider myself well within the target market for AOW III, as I mostly play games along the RPG-Strategy spectrum.As much as I hate to say it, I agree entirely with the top-rated negative review (by dacasonic). AOW III isn't bad, it just lacks depth. There are way too few units (really just one type of : light infantry, heavy, infantry, archer, cleric, light cavalry, heavy cavalry, trebuchet for everyone + 4 class units?), the research is one-dimensional (unlock a handful of units, terraforming and some spells), tactical spells are somewhat varied, but can't be used nearly enough and don't feel impactful due to a (in my opinion) mediocre resource system....In essence, my biggest qualm with the game is how little there is to look forward to. In HOMM, I look forward to unlocking level 5 spells, top-tier creatures or upgrading my hero, because those things immediately feel impactful and rewarding. In Shogun II, I can't wait to get those hero samurais on the field or finish a massive citadel in a border city. In civilization, reaching milestones (wonders, key techs, even your first settler) feels bloody great and is immediately rewarding gameplay-wise. Even in Fallen Enchantress, a second-tier X4 game, upgrading towns, levelling heroes and reaching certain research milestones feel rather gratifying and makes the player want to go on ""one more turn"".There is no equivalent in AOW III. Cities don't feel worth caring about (and it's a drag to keep them from getting overtaken by sneaky flying invaders). There are no great projects to feel excited about. Units are obtained early and the game turns into a variety-less grind within an hour of its start.Maybe the game could have been salvaged by a better hero progression and XP distribution system, to give the player something worth caring about. Levelling up heroes (XP earned when attacking other units) will grant a few points to invest in simple stats or underwhelming perks (20% resistance to an element). A talent tree with meaningful incremental investments (see shogun II, or even fallen enchantress...) coudl have helped the game a lot.I played AOW III on a mid-level laptop bought a year ago (well within reccomended specs), and the game ran rather poorly after a while. Naturally, this could be a problem on my end."
76561198015907664,Recommended,226840,18786247,"Posted: 31 October, 2015",all,Baalzebul,"EDIT:I have well over 1000 hours into this game (drat!) and every time I think of putting it down, I keep coming back.  It's been a long time since a game grabbed me like this one.  Great game!  replayabiliy is insane.WOW!Short review:  If you have any doubts from the trailers and are thinking ""Yeah, I want to get this game.""  You are probably right and do so immediately.For a bit more detail:I'm not even more than 170 turns on a big map,I can already tell you that this is an awesome game.At first I thought it was just going to be another 4x clone, which are also great, don't get me wrong, but it's a lot cooler than a lot of games I have played.The thing that sets it apart to me is that IT'S DEEP.  And while production and exloration and exploitaing are still the core of the game, there are a LOT of other elements that you REALLY have to consider if you are going to win.  It's much less of a numbers game and a lot more of a strategy game like CHESS.  It is mainly an empire conquest game as well.  There IS diplomacy, but you best be prepared to back that up with force.  It's not really a builder game, but you can totally turtle up if you want to.  If you want to survive in the world you have to maintain your empire.  And thats' before you even meet other players on the max size map.First off, you have to create your game.  As per most 4x games, there are a ton of options.There are at least 4 starting modes ranging from nothing but a city builder and a couple of military units, to having a fairly established state with big armies so you can go right to combat if you want!Next, you get to create your LEADER.  Your leader has a class, and a race. You can completely customize this leader just like an MMO or RPG. There are several classes and several races so that is a lot of options and there are both racial AND class bonuses.  All the classes are ""rock paper scissors"".  They all have different strengths and weakneeses and they are designed to be equal, if different.  I haven't confirmed how balanced they are yet.  But if you want voral bunny rabbits defending your city, Hobbit Druid has it!  In addition to that, you can style your charcter as you want, create your own flag and colors.  You get to choose 3 major abilities for your leader, such as the power to summon fire elementals out a pool of many!  You feel an imediate connection with the character.When you get in the game, it's EASY to pick up if you have any experience with a 4x game and even novices can probably figure it out if they click enough things and there are tool tips on everything.  It was very easy for me to pick up.The maps are great looking, but the cool part is that there are Volcanic, plagues, frost, and I think a couple of more types of territory and the TERRITORIES are ALSO rock paper scissors for the RACES of your leader and heros, and this factors into the game.  If you send anti volcanic troops into volcanic territory they are going to be far less efficient because moral will be low.  Things matter in this game.Another actually cool thing is that there AREN'T these giant research build trees to go through.  You can upgrade a city to max pretty quick in easy mode, which I am playing now in order to get a better handle on the game, but I'm sure the STRATEGY racks up quick.  There are like 3 levels for most abilites.  If you want to park your city and just produce mana you can do that.  Some units can fight on water.  Heroes can and do level up, and units can gain veterancy.Build cues are kept to a maximum of 5 cue items, either research or unit production.  Yes, it means you will visit your cue more often, but it works in this game because there are less actual cities on the map with an even spread.  There aren't a lot of city upgrades, so you can blow through them pretty quick.  BUT each of them matter a LOT.  You have to research archers if you want archers.  If you want to build a weapn forge (which crafts actual items for your heros) you have to research it first as expected.  There were about maybe 15 unit types under the hobbit units. (give or take).Armies are also streamlined because you can only have a maxium of 6 units per army (at least in the game I am playing, not sure if you can change that, but I don't think so.  This is GOOD because you are far less concerned with how BIG your armies are, but WHERE they are and what units are in them!Another thing is that each hero or your leader in the game has their own character sheet and as they gain levels you can spend points on any NUMBER of spells and abilities and you actually USE these abilities in combat!  There is ALSO a ""diablo like"" item page complete with a bag, and character outfitting, and you can send items from one hero to another.   The time it takes to do that is based on the distance of the heroes from each other.  So all the gear AND the spells make this hero or charcter very unique and deployable for specifc roles in an army.IN addition to that you have a SPELL BOOK which keeps each of the spell abilties of all of your heroes in combat and also GLOBAL spells that you can use to rain fire down units, or convert plague land to fertile forests for example.  You have to SHARE mana between the strategic spells and the close combat spells so it has to be managed wisely!  You learn spells by using research points (candles!) and there are many of them!  You can only cast a certain number of strategic spells per turn, depending on what they are.Also, the spells are somewhat dictated by RACE and CLASS!  So the spellbook is different for each game.  But some classes are bad at magic and a lot less effectve with less options.  The Warlord class for example.  But they make up for that with better armor and weapons and archers.In addition to your basic units that you produce, when you are successful Heros offer to join, and you can have them join you for a one time fee (I think all units have maintence fees, as expected).  Once a hero joins you, they get a character sheet EXACTLY like your Leader's charcater sheet.  Every hero you get is randomized based off race, class, and abilities so they are all UNIQUE.  Sometimes you can win a unit in battle, or a random unit to town will join you.The map is filled wtih independants and non-player kingdoms.  They can be hostile or neutral.  If you try and conquer them, some will run but some will fight.  Best be prepared if you want  to win, but stay close enough to your cites or a dragon might blow through and mess up your day!  Sometimes there is an opportunity for them to run, and you can choose between killing them or letting them run.  If you let them run you get good alignment and if you kill them you get evil.  Yes, there are good and evil abilities available when you spec your leader and for your heros.So basically, between the several terrain types, the rock paper scissors aspect of the heros and leader as well as chaning the compositon of each 6 unit army, you get BAZILLIONS of combinations, and all of the race units are themed for that race like the Hobbit Eagle Rider.  This means just a crazy amount of replayability.Finally, the COMBAT is VERY cool!  When you zoom in to the battle (IF you choose to manually fight it out) it's an area themed for the place it is.  I went in to one battle zone in a shrine and the objects decorating the shrine created obstacles that had to be worked around in the fight!  Terrain IN the fights is absolutely factors into game play.  Flanking and charging are ALSO part of the game.  If you have a hero on a mount you can charge into an enemy.  Each spellcaster can cast 1 spell per turn, so the combat really revolves around all those abilties you chose for your character.Anyway, it's all amazing.  If you like strategy games OR RPGS OR 4x genre games, you will very likely like this one.I see many hours of gaming awesomeness ahead."
76561198065980912,Recommended,226840,25819264,"Posted: 2 October, 2016",all,2134565(RNG),"9 / 10This is combat oriented 4x game. or more like little combat dedicated 4x game smiliar to HOMM or civilizations.Graphics are ok, music and sound effects are kinda cool game play really feels great.The game lacks some empire menagements  when it comes to empire building like other 4x games like Cilvilzations. Few choices you can make , few buildings you can build , and economic stuff game is too simplifed and shallow. And i have to say it is disappointing.But when it comes to combat , the game has the best combat mechanics. Unlike civilzation 4 combat system (And some bit from civilization 5) which luck plays major role in the game and you have little control about the combat itself, this game has some edge. You re no longer waiting for outcome after just throwing dice. Instead you actively engage in combat , and you can make a lot of tactial choices in combat. It feels like heroes of might and magic combat style but it has some more advaced combat mechanics and introduced some nice concepts to battle filed. You can flank your enemy , use special talents , you can bait them out... etcAnd yea this makes the game difficult to learn somewhat and could be little confusing but this is much better thanYou just attack the target and waiting for the outcome and saying like ""Oh crappp my modern infantry just got owned by pikemen , the odds were 99% purely because the luck turned out♥♥♥♥♥♥♥quot;I really still hated some luck based combat mechanics like ""Chance for your spell failure 40%"" and pesky halflings who evades 10% of attacks. but i think they removed a lot of luck based thing in the game. Theres still some things are totally governed by the luck but its less often and less frustrating then other simmliar games.The game units feels like AOE 3 , the races are unique and features simmliar units but the each races got some little bit of tweaks ""Goblin pikemen has the life drain and much stronger then others , while the elven one has the lightning attack , Draconian pike legions can fly"" and theres quite noticable amonunt of themThe hero / leader customizaions are quite remakable as well . you can experiment with a lot of magic / economic / combat oriented specialization and it is really fun playing with different races / classes  / specailizationThis game requires several hours of game play to learn basic stuff but it will be rewarding as you get better and gameYou can expect a lot of from game if you re fan of TBS like civilzations .P.S if you re planning to get just 1 expasion pack i recommend Eternal lord one it has the more volume then the other one."
,Recommended,226840,23199323,"Posted: 25 May, 2016",all,Thyrork,"To say I like this game would be an understatement. With over five hundred hours on record, and a healthy amount of those hours spent playing multiplayer with members of the Something Awful community, and most if not all the hidden things explored, I still find joy in loading this game up and taking a necromancer out for a spin as I turn the entire world into an open grave. I still find myself impressed by the swathe of modding content, adding more hours to the lifespan of this game.On that note, it is worth emphasising,Please get thecollectionand not just the base game.Eternal Lords is worth the difference alone, while golden realms is also a really strong expansion. The Delux DLC is a nice bonus but the real prize is Eternal Lords. Necromancers are a very fun class but Tigrans and Frostlings are also great races to play as well.Now, lets discuss comparisons. This is not Civ, nor is it Endless Legend. In both of those games, you have a few other ways to win, you can play as an economic powerhouse who wins by driving everyone into a happy friendship circle. This is not how Age of Wonders 3 plays. War is here. War is how you win.* Drive your enemies leaders to their knees and take their thrones.* Find the seals of power, drive away the guardians and stand upon them, facing rival kingdoms and angry elementals until you master control of the place of power and turn it upon your foes in victory.* Unite races together and ignite beacons of unity, driving your enemies mad with envy as you prove your mastery of diplomacy by the sword as well as the tongue.You do not win Age of Wonders by becoming king of treasure hill or cutting into other cultures like a knife, You win age of wonders by the sword and the spell. You will lead mighty armies of golems, backed by the might of goblin riflemen. Armies of high elf berserkers, howling furious challenge. Armies of frostling spellcasters, standing alongside summoned beasts. Armies of undead humans, still wielding spiritual fire even while bound to your dreadful will.Heroes will be at your command to be equipped by the prizes you rip from ancient tomb and bandit-infested farmstead. From swords to rings to mounts, all waiting to be claimed and lost when your rivals finally kill your promising champion and scatter their prizes to the wind.You win in Age of Wonders in battle, and battle is what this game does very well. On this note I advise checking youtube for a few videos of the combat. Words don’t really capture it, nor do comparisons. Best to see for yourself.I think by this point I’ve said enough. There are other reviews that go into more technical details then I have, I am simply writing from a very bias place of love.There are battles to be won, cities to be courted, inn’s to be explored, caves to be feared, lairs to be cleared, heroes to be leveled, heroes to regret losing, items to be won, armies to be lost, beacons to be lit, seals to be defended and grand spells to be cast. Get to it."
