76561198032195639,Recommended,226840,9688926,"Posted: 31 March, 2014",all,ActionJesus,"I have played Age of wonders game in the past so I am pretty familier on the game play of these type of games, let me start and say this game is the best graphical of the lot.   Now that I have that out of the way the detail that the developers have put in this game is pretty impressive.  Each individual unit makeup and descriptions are pretty well done as well pretty funny on some of the unit discriptions, similar to Warcraft humor.  The tactical combat is a pleasure to do even though there is a option for auto-resolve. I wouldn't suggest auto resolving too much unless your cut for time, and this game is not really made to be rushed and get it done game.  Like the old saying goes its good to smell the flowers sometimes and you should do this in this game because the animation and tactical combat is a thing of beautify.  The unit detail as you battle is so detailed I had to zoom all the way to appreciate the orc's armor and color scheme,  it's that good.You can tell they put alot of love and effort in this game.  There is so so much detail besides the units makeup, terrain, heroes, etc. etc...  I just can't go thru all of it, it was pretty much worth my hard earn money.   Gameplay is very addictive and the story is interesting and keeped me involved.Now everything isn't perfect like when siege units break down walls.  Its hard to see from the animation that the wall was destroyed or not.  I keeped attacking the same wall because of it.  Only way I knew that the wall was destroyed was that I accidently moved a unit past the castle and it moved threw the wall.  Thats probably going to be patched since this is fairly a new game.  I am sure there are other bugs but nothing I have played so far that crashes the game.  Its pretty stable and the turns are rather quick after you finish your round.  I would say it takes few secs for the next round, thats really fast, which is pretty impressive compaired  to game like Rome Total War 2. It seemed like forever to wait for your next turn the Total War game.  Yes these two games are different but just trying to point out that turns are pretty quick and fluid in Age of Wonders 3.All in all I would highly recommend this game to any turn base strategist and fantasy buff.  The intereface is so easy I believe it might attract a wider audience besides the aftermentioned gamers.  Yes, this will suck your time like no other.  I went straight 4 hours playing and didnt even notice the time go by, thats how enjoyable this game is.  Just smell the flower and trust me dont rush threw this flower bed or you will miss the beauty of this game.NOTE: I purchased the game and was not a Beta tester or a employee of them. lol"
,Recommended,226840,27102472,"Posted: 24 November, 2016",all,Mastuck,"So, I nominated this game for some Steam Award and now I have to write a review for 25XP. Deal with it! Still, I'm going to write a full review as someone wo has nearly 400 hours in Age of Wonder 2: Shadowmagic, and... well, a lot less hours in Civ 5.So what is Age of Wonders 3?Age of Wonders 3 is a turn based Strategy game strongly focused around combat, in a pretty standard fanatasy setting. You have elfs, orcs, goblins, halflings and some more unique races like fronstlings and draconians for example. You play as a highly customizable wizard, learning spells and taking over cities, you can upgrade to build stronger and more units, either by producing them in the cities or summoning them with magic.You have multiple classes for your wizard, that kind of work based on the rock paper scissors principle.You'll be able to recruit heros, who can cast some spells as well, and whom you can level up and equip, just like your wizard. Unlike in the previous Age of Wonders game you have the option for your heroes, that if they die in battle, they'll still life on afterwards, unless you lose the bettle entirely. But then you can just resurrect them, using a spell, everyone gets sooner or later. This makes things much less frustrating for those who wish so.The other big new thing in AoW3 is flanking. In AoW2 you could come in with a few strong units and just ♥♥♥♥ up a whole army of individualy weaker units with ease, unless you enemie had a big defensive advantage. Flanking gives you new tactical method to make your numbers count, if used well, and it makes some stealthy units more viable, by focusing their skills on this tool, not just having invisibility or concealment on the worldmap.Yes, there is a worldmap and a ""new"" map for each battle. Playing CIV5 after AoW is the least satisfying thing in regards of combat ever. It's like playing ludo after falling in love with chess. You can fire with archers or priests from the top of your city wall, while the enemie sends massive wallbreakers to tear down your gates. Meanwhile his flying unity just pass the wall, trying to take out your raged units. As your last archer dies you cast a massive firestorm for lots of damage on every unit on the battlefield, including your own ones. This is combat.Now there are some cons I'll have to point out.First of all I am not a fan of the campain. As much as I'd like to play it, the missions are just annoying to me. I can't really explayin why, sorry. But I've never liked the campain in any AoW game, while there are many others who loved them. So most of the time i'm just playing randoms maps.The second thing I'd like to point out is a point that occurs in every round I'm playing. It's the point where you are (if you're winning) reaching superiority in a game it becomes boring. They implemented the option for leaders to surrender to you, which I really appreciate, but if you play a 4-player match and took over the cities of 2 of them already, the last enemie is pretty boring to defeat most of the times. That's why I rarely ever finish a game.The third thing are the difficulty settings for the AI. The AI cheats on higher difficulties. They get way more resources, combat bonuses agains independent units, like for example a group of dwarfs protecting a mine, and other stuff. That's not a good way to create difficulty in my opinion.And at last the DLC problem. No, I think the pricing is ok, but I also think they are mandatory for a good experience. The base game just feeld a bit empty.But now a quick sum up of all the great stuff, and belive me, there is a lot!The combat is great, and if your Army of Angels has to fight a pack of wolves you can just let the battle fight out automatically. The new class-system is a welcoming difference. The environment looks gorgeous, even on (most) random generated maps. I still prefer the soundtrack of AoW2 but it's still great in AoW3. Never had any problems with online play. The spells are great. The customization options for the leaders give a lot of variety and a lot of different options for tactics.To sum it up.Age of Wonders 3 is a great turn based game that lacks the economical complexity of games like Civ, but provides a superior tactical combat experience in a good looking fantasy setting.8,9/10 because I can play as a goblin druid and it's great!"
,Recommended,226840,10021535,"Posted: 4 May, 2014",all,walpurgisnacht,"I have always loved both the mythological turn based strategy war games and the Civilization games, so when I saw this I went for it.  Man, I am not disappointed.  Personally, it keeps my interest better than Civ V because of the unpredictable variance of the random maps.  I started playing the recommended campaign, but that was right when I got it, and needed to learn how to play this game.  I quickly switched to the random maps and have been having a blast with the curve balls this game throws at you.  I took over a dwelling of giants at one point and was carefully upkeeping it before producing a giant unit due to the expensive maintenence when suddenly a city on my outer borders got attacked by a very nasty undead dragon.  The dwellings are cool if you can take them over, but are fierce opponents.  If you take over or are joined by an independent city of another race, you can make units of that race.   Learning the game is an experience that increases its replayability.  At first I thought goblins were unfairly weak, but after playing other races, I learned some goblin units are pretty darn superior for their type.  You can basically play the way you want - if you want to be warlike, go ahead and invade and break treaties, or whatnot.  There are rewards for getting an evil alignment as well as good if you want to try more diplomatic methods such as doing quests to absorb cities.  I can't say much about the campaigns or the multiplayer at this point, as I am having too much fun with the random maps to try them yet.  I totally recommend this game if you like Civ games and myth-related turn based strategies."
