,Recommended,226840,30813989,Posted: 29 March,all,T2TL,"Pros and cons at the bottomshort version:This game is the best turn based strategy game i have ever played (i have played a lot of them). I have hundreds of hours in offline play on this one. If you like fully customizable heroes (very very customizable, almost rpg like), deep tech trees and xp earning units that end up forming an elite guard in your army or gets thrown away as cannon fodder just to be replaced with more, then this game is a must. Graphics are good, gameplay is very good and music is absolutely excellent.Longer version:This just might be the best turn based strategy game of all time, rivalling the likes of Heroes of might and magic 3 and warlords 2. AOW series can be described as being a mix of those two games series as this game features city specific tech trees, hero classses and races, fully customizeable heroes, global and tactical spells, xp for all units and heroes, income and upkeep, tactical battles, heroless armies, quests, random events and the list goes on for pages. The campaign story rocks from the very first game in the series and no less in the last. Scenarios feel like mini campaings and the map generator works very well. Races and classes have clear different feels to them and are well balanced with the option to build some badass heroes and armies.An example is the match between the rogue class and the dreadnaught class, one is based on nimble movement and cruel backstabs while the other is based on mass destruction by steamdriven warmachines. The AOE from the dreadnaughts death macines would prove unbeatable for the light, but fast rogue units if not for their scoundrels ability to sprint through the incoming fire and sabotage those same engines causing tremendous damage. There is no such thing as a fair fight against a rogue and so such thing as a casualty free battle against dreadnaughts.This is an immersive fantasy strategy game with deep tactics and rock, paper, scissor counters with near endless options for combination and no two games need look alike. The fantasy setting and campaing story with a red line going from the very first release in the series to the last of the DLC (which btw is well worth the purchase on sale if youre short on cash). Your hero pick up where you left him in every mission of the campaign making you increasingly badass and without any linear progression as it is entirely up to the player how to build him or her.Pros:-Game is awesome-Very good campaigns with thorough and exciting tutorial elements in the start-Turnbased with simultaneous play options with the turn ending when all players press end-Music (really).-You will never try all combinations of races, classes and hero skills nor will you want to stop trying.-So customizable that style and taste comes into play.-Deep morale system and buff/debuff.-Alignment (good/evil/neutral) is earned in every game by actions.-Unit alignments.-Race relations and specific faction relations also mostly earned.-Can be played in ""simple"" mode by making easy setups and disabling things.-Great campaign with red line from the very first game, without it being a requirement that you have played the earlier games.-Very dynamic once you get the hang of how to do things properly.-The little things does matter, they make up the balance which allows deeper undestanding for better tactics.-Has settler mode with empty maps where the empires have to be built from scratch.-Have a ton of modes and random events and basically endless things that can make every single game significantly different even on the same map.-Sometimes trying that thing you didnt think worked turns out to work very well and continues to surprise and reward creativity-Has many good scenarios which play out like small campaigns-Classes and races have very different, but balanced, strengths allowing any well executed approach to work effectively.Cons:-Very large maps can accumulate a little too much management for some peoples taste, though it can be circumvented by teching and planning well (making 5 dragons instead of 50 footmen, less units is less management).-Did not release a sequel the minute i finished the campaign (making me wait, like why?)-Can be confusing if you try to understand everything at first, play the first campaign first which turns this into a pro-Some classes like Rogue or Sorceror/Sorceress can be a hazzle to fight if you dont force the fight onto your terms and instead let them harass you, this can be a pro if you like being that one ;)"
