,Recommended,226840,17421721,"Posted: 6 August, 2015",all,fize4ever,"This entry is a fantastic --albeit different-- return to the series. If you want a turn-based high-fantasy strategy game, look no further than AoW.However, I can say without a flinch that if you wanted to truly enjoy Age of Wonders, you should start with the earlier games. As good as this game is, it's nowhere near earlier instalments. No, this is not nostalgia kicking in, I'm actually playing Age of Wonders: Shadow Magic right now, and it has more races, more units (some will tell you AoW 3 has more units, but they'll omit the fact that a decent portion of them are literal copy-pastes).The old games stick to a recognized lore, so you literally will not see Angel Goblins (I'm not kidding, they're called ""exalted"".. the struggle is real), Elvish trolls (""Warbreeds""), and other ridiculous units.Bottom of line, this game is great for what it is, an attempt to revive a highly praised franchise, and although it falls short in many ways, it is still a good game for all it's worth. Fans of AoW will definitely like this entry, while newcomers may shy away from the bizarre setup.Plus, the developers are really trying to appease everyone, and they're constantly supporting and updating the game. They can literally cash in and make a new game with all the updates and DLC they've done, but they chose to support this already existing game. Triumph is no big studio, so this says a lot.Thank you Triumph, this is a good game. Although, we're still hoping for an SM-tier entry. :-)"
