76561197997109962,Recommended,226840,9925516,"Posted: 24 April, 2014",all,goredancer,"Considering the good/bad comments about AOW, there is not much left to say apart from:PRO:-This game is a total BLAST in Multiplayer - even in hotseat mode when everybody is watching your moves (paranoia reigns !)- People complaining about the lack of depth (economy): Name a *good* (like CIV4 or Endless Space) game where the economical micromanagement was'nt just a time consuming boredom-factor once you got past the number crunching..- AOW3 IS heavily combat-focused - and in that discipline it shines on every level. The amount of tactical decisions to be made (terrain, movement, stats, buffs, debuffs, resistances etc.) combined with clever army builing is JUST RIGHT to let this game FLOW. In this regard, AOW3 succeeds where all the other titles (HoMM 4-6, Disciples, Fallen Enchantress) have failed miserably.CONTRA:- The Number 1 Mistake of new Players (and obviously the reason for a lot of bad tempered ""reviews"") is the misinterpretation of the way the units are represented (HP/DMG-wise). FOLKS ! The Number of 3d-Models in a Unit is JUST A REPRESENTATION of the Hitpoints - where low-tier units have i.e. 5 figures and high-tier units just one model..so: no, once the Orc Shock Trooper slot looses a model (HP) it does not inflict less damage. It's all a matter of interpretation.My real Contra with this is that the devs did not consider the necessity of explaining this is in some sort of tutorial. It's 2014 and the kids are used to playing stupid crap where everything is chewed for them...what a good 4x game does is leaving some room for imagination, only visualizing what is necessary to establish the mood. But it's a sad fact that , in order to sell these concepts to the masses - you have to *educate* them a little bit- Diplomacy. Just plain boring. What i'm really missing is an AI that displays total irrational reactions (a goblin druid declaring war on you just because you captured his favoured neutral tavern; an allied dwarven theocrat who is a racist ♥♥♥♥♥♥♥ and breaks the alliance because you have chosen not to migrate the last town you captured to your heroes race...you got the idea.Where everything else in TBS is about numbers and logic - diplomacy should be about lying, cheating, egos and taste - just like real world politics :)- The random Map Generator needs serious tweaking. There is some sort of ""Mountain Spaming"" on large map types with ""underground"" and even player numbers...very annoying.Bottom Line:There is always a lot of work to be done. Some Unit-Stats tweaking here, some AI-Polishing there. Regarding the overall game design, AOW3 does it right. There have been lots of discussions about the typical TBS issues: Balancing the time exposure / gameflow ratio; how to avoid the stack of doom, complexity vs. laid back indulgence. The fundamentals are here, they play very well and boy - do they look good. With some more effort, this will be the best fantasy-themed TBS-Game since the days of MoM..."
76561198006617832,Recommended,226840,17378495,"Posted: 3 August, 2015",all,Dayve,"I really like this game and I think it's underrated. It consists of two parts; strategic world map and turn-based battles. I'll briefly explain each one here. There's a campaign mode which is fun but my favourite part of the game is the random map which you can customize the hell out of. There's an incredible amount of options for you to customize your own skirmish game. You can have a very short one with a small map, with huge amounts of resources and starting with large armies, or you can have a large map with lots of civilizations, slow research times, few starting resources (and few resources on the map) and so forth. You can even customize the terrain if you want to take the time, so there are a lot of options to suit your fancy.You'll choose a race (human, orc, goblin, elf, etc.) and a class (warlord, theocrat, dradnought, sorcerer, etc) for your civilization. Each race has specific strengths and weaknesses and each class is very very different. A warlord civilization for example are focused on strong conventional armies, a dreadnought civilizationis focused on industry and powerful siege engines, a sorcerer civilization is magic based and so on. Your starting hero (which is like a leader of your overall civ and can be used as a general in your armies) will determine the class of your civilization, so choosing a warlord hero will make your civilization a warlord civ, but you can recruit other heroes of other classes as the game progresses.World map - this part of the game is very much like Civilization V and is wonderfully simple and easy to learn. You'll begin with a settler (or a city depending on what options you chose to start with) and your settler will set up your first city, you can choose where. Cities produce gold, production and mana resources and you can build city upgrades and recruit units from them. There are resource structures on the map and if they are inside your city's borders then they give bonuses to gold, production, mana or research. Gold is used to build upgrades in your cities, recruit units and has some functions in diplomacy (yes there's diplomacy with independent cities and other civs), production is very simple - if your city is producing 20 production and a barracks takes 100 production to build, you'll build it in 5 turns. Mana is used to cast spells and knowledge works like production except it's used to research new spells/technologies. Your cities also produce population and grow from small villages to huge metropolises. There's happiness and allignment too - if a city is happy they will throw a party in honour of you which nets you some gold, and alignment is good and evil (and neutral) and is affected by things you do on the map, such as attacking independent cities or letting enemies run when they don't want to fight you. The strategic map is also quite beautiful. Think of it as Civilization V with a fantasy, Lord of the Rings-type feel to it.The other part of the game is the battle map. You create your armies on the strategic map and when they meet enemies the game loads the battle map. The battle map is turn based and hex based with flanking penalties. You have a variety of units to command, each with very different skills (like necromancers that can raise the dead to fight for you and curse enemies) and your hero can cast spells that he/she has learned. It's all quite easy to learn but takes a bit of time to master.As I said I think this game is underrated and it's definitely worth buying if you like 4X type games."
76561198021468634,Recommended,226840,9717758,"Posted: 3 April, 2014",all,Zakon,"An excellent tactical wargame. It plays like a combination of Might & Magic and Civilization, however it differs significantly from the both of them.First off: do not be fooled, Civilization fans. If you're looking for a fantasy equivalent of Civilization, this isn't going to perfectly scratch that itch. While it does have highly customizable kingdoms (with races and themes to pick from - steampunk elves and druidic dwarves are both possible, for example), the kingdoms themselves serve no purpose except to produce combat units. There is no need to improve tiles, and while civilization happiness is a factor, it's generally not an issue unless enemy empires start using magic to lower happiness within your cities. The biggest thing that hampers it from being 'fantasy Civ' however, is that there is no tech tree and there are no victory conditions other than to defeat your enemies, or attempt to form an Alliance between them.That said, if you were the sort of Civilization player who preferred scrapping with barbarian tribes and winning the game through domination of your enemies, this game may actually end up being a better alternative. It plays similarly to Civilization V, but it is entirely a wargame. It provides roaming bands of monsters to fight, and small dungeons to explore with your army and recover magical items to equip your heroes with. The independant cities (this game's version of City-States from Civ V) provide quests which can give magical item rewards, and can even reward you with joining your empire, giving you access to unique units such as fey and giants.The game turns into a Might & Magic-esque tactical RPG when in combat, providing a large grid with terrain to utilize for cover and flanking. Might & Magic players should be happy with what is provided here, though they should keep in mind that battlefields are typically much larger than the chessboard-esque M&M battlefields. Army sizes are also typically much smaller, with most engagements having no more than six units on either side. Only city battles can exceed this limit.I highly recommend this game to M&M fans, fans of tactical RPGs, and fans of Civilization who enjoy the Domination victory condition. However, Civ players who enjoy nonviolent victory conditions should look elsewhere."
