76561198035653328,Recommended,226840,20263457,"Posted: 3 January, 2016",all,redricofirst,"This is not a Civilization V with magic around it, and before buying this game you should have this in mind.he city managing part id far too simple. You cannot modify the environment around it, all what is left is to choose which building or unit will be next, and if you will use a special resource. It is really a sad point, because everything is ready in the game to do this, so it is obviously a game design choice. Amateurs of city builder will not find this enough.Actually almost everything is focused around the combat. When enemy units meet, you can choose to resolve automatically or manually. If you choose manually, you then have a turn-based hexagon grid where you deploy your units, and where the deployment zones are functions of the relative locations o the units on the main map when the encounter started. This is not the big thing, but a nice idea. For the rest of the fight, it is dejà vu, so I will not go in details. But if you liked Heroes of Might & Magic, you get a lite version of the fighting encounter. In the long run it gets repetitive.You've got a campaign, which without being a paragon of originality is not bad at all.The graphics or the main map, are really nice, and the game runs without problems on Linux.It is hard to either recommend or not this game. I would have preferred a game more about management, but that said, it is not a bad game. If you like turn-based hex-grid battles in a fantasy world, you're a future customer."
,Recommended,226840,28723432,"Posted: 27 December, 2016",all,Kyutaru,"Age of Wonders 3 is not a game like Civilizations. They share things in common but the troop lineup is ripped straight from typical RTS games. AoW3 is a turn-based RTS complete with base building, buying stables to produce cavalry, buffing the units with upgrades and tech research (which takes time to build just as it does in an RTS) and spamming your favorite units across the map as early as possible.You'll explore tons of treasure sites, find optimal places to build a new base, and wrack up tons of experience and artifacts for your heroes. In that sense it's a competitive PVE game since optional autobattles and economy management can make the game about who has the stronger army as opposed to the smarter tactics. Units move extremely fast across the map unlike Civ and you can have your enemy's army invisible and at your doorstep without warning. Hope you left some defenders or you just lost your capital.Base rushing, expansion, tech research, build order, unit synergy, all important RTS elements and brought here for your amusement. Spy on the enemy with scouts to find out what he's building then build the perfect counter units that are essentially invincible against that type of enemy. Best part is that if you play for a VERY long time you will eventually get access to every race in the game by conquering neutral cities. So you can design your ideal endgame army and semi-reliably get it every game as long as you explored enough to find the right cities.If you played Heroes of Might and Magic then you know the drill.  Awesome game!"
