76561198136072271,Not Recommended,226840,15017395,"Posted: 23 March, 2015",all,Teralitha,"I have mixed feelings on this game.   Ill start by saying that I own all the previous AOW games and have played them through many times and also multiplayer.1. A number of downgraded changes were made from aow 1-2 in the area of gameplay, seemingly in favor of better graphics.2. The sound tracks from the older versions were better, IMO.   Plus the lack of a customizable playlist that existed in all other AOW games bothered me.   I had asked a dev if they could implement the customized playlist like the older games have and they did say they would see if it could be done...3. The change from 8 units to 6 units per army...  I cant say I liked that.   It made the combat less diverse tactical. They ought to have increased to 10.  But this was probably done because of the more intense graphics and in battle animations/particle effects wouldnt allow for good framerates.  More units in a battle would probably make it unplayable except for the best PC's.3. Flying or floating units are no different than any other now.  Basically a unit with wings doesnt actually fly anymore.  I understand why they changed it, but they didnt have to.4. There is a very steep power curve between the different teirs in aow3.  Too steep.  Any lesser units are basically useless later.  In AOW1-2 even a tier 1 unit still had a chance to survive vs a tier 4.  Now? no way.  The power gap is too much, and you only get 6 units per army.  If you could have more it would be economical to bring more cheap units to a battle and only a few expensive ones.5. The heroes in aow3 are somewhat weaker.  Your armor and resists have a negligible effect.  And your heroes are heavily targeted.  They are most just for show and spellcasting but cant really fight very well.  In aow1-2, your heroes really were heroes.  In this game they are wall flowers...6.  Every time your units get attacked they turn to face the attacker, after the fact. This facing change that happens every time a unit is hit is really dumb.  Your units can be attacked from the rear several times because of it, and it really makes your heroes feel useless when it happens to them and enemies always seem to focus on your heroes too.7. Castle and tower walls are just graphics now.  They are pretty useless for slowing down the attackers and several times I felt that playing defence behind a wall was actually detrimental and did little to stop attacking forces.  In this regard I feel like a good defensive strategy is a moot point.  In aow 1 and 2, seiging a walled city or tower was pretty difficult, as it should be.  You had to build and bring siege weapons in order to get past walls.  There were not many unit types that could climb or fly over walls.  And you needed ranged attacks or your own flying units(or magic/spider webs/druid entangle and other - such diversity that was stripped from aow3...) to deal with flying units. AoW3 just has too may ways for units to circumvent or destroy the walls too quickly and easily. Its like the walls and gates arent even there.  Also in aow1-2 cities had a number of magicaI defenses you could unlock and build.  It really made sieging a city quite an ordeal.  I resorted to using the auto battle instead of torturing myself....8. Magic domains in aow 3 are also another moot point now.  Your leader should not be able to use any magic outside it like it was in aow 1-2.  I feel like this magic domain mechanic is anti AOW, which has always been about wizards and their towers and domains and their armies being powerless outside of them unless the leader or hero was physically present.If you never played an AOW game before, these flaws probably wont be noticable and you might like it.But if your like me, the differences and dumbed down mechanics from aow1-2 will make you not enjoy this game as much as the originals and possibly even regret buyng it.  Ive tried playing through the campaigns twice now, and the story is interesting, but the dumbed down gameplay turns me off and I get tired of it."
