,Recommended,226840,31533573,Posted: 3 May,all,nuclearunicorn7,"The best way I would describe this game is a mix of the city building from Civilization, research and leader building similar to Master of Magic, and the map exploration of Heroes of Might and Magic. This may seem like a strange combo at first, but I feel that it works incredibly well and I think it's safe to say that this mixture causes me to immensely enjoy this series and what I have played of this specific title so far has yet to counteract this notion. This game has its own variations on these mechanics of course, but the overall structure of these parts is like the games mentioned.I should mention that these comparisons stop at the combat which is the biggest part that makes this game stand out from the others mentioned. The combat takes you into a seperate battle screen where the gameplay becomes turn based tactics. The biggest focus of the combat is in the balancing of movements and attacks. Each unit starts a turn with 3 attacks. That number decreases based on the amount of hexes moved with you always having one attack at the maximum range moved. When you use an attack ability, you will use up all your attacks to use it and you cannot move afterward which is why I use the term ""attacks"" as opposed to action points given that term usually implies a little bit more flexibility (despite that technically being the term used in game). There are things like abilities that take up multiple attacks to use and abilities that will only go off once no matter the number of attacks left, but that's still the main focus.This combat is sumplemented by sheer variety. The number of spells, units, unit modifiers, damage types, and abilities is so large that it adds a lot of complexity to this combat that's relatively simple at its base. That's not to mention the variety gained from the out of combat aspects, which has it's own variety of spells, buildings, things to interact with, and the ways certain races deal with the environment that there is seemingly large amounts of content to go through even with just the base game.While I do not have any of the expansions to give you a good idea of the full experience, based on my research they seem to take the HoMM route with expansions and just add more stuff as opposed to the huge mechanical changes brought in by the expansions in games like Civ V so I feel that I have a fairly decent idea of what the mechanics of the game are like based on my previous experience with the series and current time with this game."
