76561198229231924,Recommended,226840,26716976,"Posted: 20 November, 2016",all,teufel_barde,"Age of wonders 3 is another installment into the age of wonder series, a fantasy, 4X game with hex grid-turn based combat.Now, normally when i write these reviews, i'd go into depth about the plot or the world or both. But, considering that i spent a significant amount of time playing against AI and some friends in multiplayer, and avoided the single player aspect of it all together, i cannot give you a decent summery beyond saying that the common wealth, a joint group of races, have taken over a large section of the world, there is a court of elves who have not joined, and in the DLC, you can explore new lands with new races, and play as a cold blooded necromancer.Age of wonders functions like any other 4X game to an extent, you are placed on a randomly generated world (customised to your tastes, with a rather extensive range of options) as your chosen hero. Each hero is of a different race, class and has different abilities, each one drastically effecting how your nation will function. You can also make your own custom hero as well. I ended up making a necromancer dark elf called thul'duarn the shadebane, a master of destruction magic and expanding. Your race effects what kinds of units you can make, what type of areas your people like to settle in and what they can build inside cities, it also effects what things increase and decrease your moral. Each city has moral, depending on a number of factors, high moral is good and can lead to festivals, increased production and free money, low moral can lead to rioting and other bad things. Your class determines what kind of spells you can use, the powers your specific hero unit can use and what special units and buildings you can make. your chosen abilities will also determine your spells, unique units and so on.From there, you build up your city, but unlike other 4X games, there is a heavy insentive to go exploring with large armies, because, all around the world there are dungeons, minor factions and free loot to pick up. The dungeons, once cleared, grant bonuses to any city that has it in its borders, the minor factions can be brought into your empire by either doing a few easy quests for them, or just crushing their city with your forces. There are also random map wide events that occur, such as the penguin king and his army of penguins.Like most 4X games you do need to research new tech, you do this with knowledge and mana, though, you can also research new spells for your hero to use. If your hero is taking place in a battle, they can cast it at normal cost, if they are not, you can pay double the mana in order to use it. These spells range anywhere from a simple fireball, to a mass raise army spell, allowing you to summon literally limitless units until the battle is over.Then there is alignment, every character starts off as neutral unless they have taken a specific specialization. From there, you can go evil or good, depending on minor choices you make in game. However, there is no reason to be evil, as it drastically decreases the moral of your people if you go too far down that road, and other nations will outright hate you for it. But on the flip side, there is only a minor penalty for declaring war, so you can happily be the nicest warmonger you want without fear.The main ways to win the game are diplomatically (have everyone agree to become your sworn ally), or via war (kill all the things to win).  Naturally, i went for war every time, because otherwise there is no way to win against human opponents unless they surrender. There is no third or forth option, like a religious victory or a science victory.At the end of the day, Age of Wonders 3 is a 4X game for warmongers, there is literally no better way to win than to swarm your enemies with units, which can get extremely boring after a while, even if the combat is very good. The moral system is nice, but there is one issue, the necromancer class. You see, necromancer controlled cities that have been turned undead are not effected by moral what so ever, meaning they don't have bonuses or penalties to anything, they are just very good at pumping out more undead. Combine this with the fact the necromancer class has access to extremely powerful units in early, mid and late game, and the fact that they have some of the best spells in the game, really breaks it. There is nothing really to concern yourself with in terms of minor details like food and your alignment either, since you are a necromancer.I found the game very fun at first, but after a few matches i really grew tired of the process and found it far too easy, even on harder settings. Its not as deep as some 4X fans might be looking for and its too shallow for new people to be able to experience all the aspects of a 4X game. The only thing i can praise is the soundtrack, just, the pieces vary in quality, alot of them are solidly ok, some bland as paste, others really enjoyable. It makes for good background for a tabletop rpg, but thats it. I wouldn't recommend this to anyone, but i wouldn't tell them to avoid it either, if i could give an ok rating, i would, but thats not possible sadly.I will tell a little story of how my necromancer won his first campaign, if only because it might help you understand how the game goes. So, off in the corner of the large map, my undead city rose from the earth and proceeded to declare the location chosen as ""fort bosturd"". Right outside my city was a hero, offering to be hired for a handful of coins, despite the fact he was a better necromancer than me. i split my armies up and roamed around the country, doing my necromancer thing, until i encountered a lovely group of faries, instead of running in terror, they greated me nicely and offered to become my allies if i killed a giant, two turns later, i had a giant corpse following me and a new ally. after a bit i turned them into part of my kingdom, and my first act as a new ruler was to convert their city into an undead one...without realizing they can't make the facilities that allow undead cities to grow. the city had a population of zero. i gifted it to my general, he seemed pleased.Jump forward about fifty turns and i had conquered about one third of the map, thanks to my amazing charisma, gleaming repulation as a merciful ruler and the massive undead horde that mindlessly agreed with me. i ran into another nation, ran by a goblin rogue called (insert ♥♥♥♥♥♥ goblin name here) the pretty. Naturally, she was smitten with me, a rotting corpse man, and we became diplomatic friends. I then ignored her and went to capture a city on my borders with my armies, which was a tougher nut to crack than i expected, losing a good number of troops. But i knew next turn i'd have it, until the goblin swooped in, stole the city from underneath me, then told me to ♥♥♥♥ off out of her lands within the next turn. my units all moved out, except for one, whom she destroyed and declared war on me. My armies were rather spread out, but i soon sorted that out, and just as i was about to murder her, she offered peace, and joined my empire, giving me a boost to peace and earning me the good alignment reward.I spread death and plague about for another fifty turns, everyone loving me as i turned them into walking corpses, when the penguin king event happened. in a few turns, i had lost two cities to penguins and was fighting off hordes of them. On that day i swore vengence against the penguin king and all his snowy followers, taking back my cities and cursing how far i had fallen behind in my conquests because of the delay. when i returned to the front, i met evil jesus. the guy who had won the true evil alignment reward, naturally, we did not get on very well, he was a theocrat, and his units could hit mine like trucks. but before he got the chance to, he surrendered to the other AI player. whom swore himself to me after i gifted him two really ♥♥♥♥♥♥ cities. and that was how i won."
