76561197973274252,Recommended,226840,10048722,"Posted: 7 May, 2014",all,Sydrian,"Having been a fan of the original two Age of Wonders titles, I picked this up. I held no real expectations, as most modern reboots of older franchises subscribe to conformed design and retain less than a desireable amount of their core originality. Oftentimes it actually alienates the core of the original fangroups. Angering at minimum a considerable amount of fans. Now... I could go on a long and verbose tangent comparing this to its predecessors, but I figure creating a category for that is better(Concept Preservation). I just hope my thoughts are enough to provide you some insight before you do or do not purchase this.Score Summary: I will start with this so you can circle back to it, and review my overall scores without distancing yourself from each scoring.Additionally, I have not tried the internet mutiplayer. I would recommend finding an opinion on that if you're looking to play competitively or with others over the internet. I typically play this hotseat style.Gameplay: 6 / 10Graphics: 8 / 10Functionality: 7 / 10Concept Presrvation: 6 / 10Overall Score: 6.75 / 10---------------------------Gameplay: 6/10Reasons for docked points.-No extended game scaling: Mechanically this could be corrected by added research point spell costs, or specialization research; Which I assume, could actually be patched in. This pretty much makes any large map a real brain drill to endure.-Limitations on customizations feel too constraining. In the end, you're playing with modules for heroes over depth and flavor. Same problem applies to craftable in game items. Raising the ceiling on  item customization and increasing customization options could radically improve this.-Really jarring moments in gameplay when moving units in combat and when trying to use commands with simultanous turns mode. Simultanous turns saves time, but often any ai or indepents will move before any player because the engine does not process multiple commands from multiple players in real time. It takes the first command entered.-Limited usefulness to mechanics of the game. Veterancy chief among them. For all the work of raising a unit naturally to high veterancy and the difficulty of preserving them in battle, the payoff doesn't even feel like it's there. It does influence things, but so marginally that there really isn't a great deal of value to even having it. The only payoffs that truly reward are those with abilities attached to them or evolutions(Don't ever expect to get those easily.) The tier system is good for informative purposes, but as a function of the game, it murders the potential fo the veterancy system. I would've recommended a alternative approach veterancy such as a higher level cap for lower tiers, because it makes sense that weaker units would develop more skills than stronger ones over time; and it would richly reward people for the effort of keeping them alive. Perhaps such a change could be patched in or added with some kind of DLC expansion.Gameplay ReviewWhy a six out of ten? Let's begin with the things I like about the game. Fundamentally, what sets this game franchise apart from others to me, is the ability to radically change the environment; This incarnation of the game doesn't just make it visual, it can have a serious impact on the strength of armies if the environment is hostile to them. Morale is a very real thing to this game, and strong positive and negative effects radically alter the behavior of the cities, armies, and heroes that you manage. Affecting or controlling everything from critical hits, to random city behaviors, desertions, and rebellions. (Positive causes surprise good presents(Sudden construction, resource bursts), negative usually means rebellious armies start spawning in the domain.)The diplomacy engine has been expanded upon slightly with npcs, with an added alignment system and other behavioral systems to ais. I found that the stronger I got, the less inclined to start a war other ai players would be. A combination of wealth, alignment, military threat, and probably a few other factors I haven't discovered largely control how neutral camps and ai players percieve and interact with you. Players can trade items, cities, forts, the right to enter borders. (If someone declares war on you, they ignore your borders presence when it comes to whether or not they can enter your area..)You can create a somewhat customizeable leader with some variances on appearance, skill setup; The lack of options and the hard cap of only 3 specializations hurt the long game. This game really feels like it thrives during a mid game situation. Early battles can be quite difficult if you don't know what you're doing, and I found myself frequently using auto combat, because of the risk it would be to try to run things myself. I'm certain that if I better knew what I was doing, life would be a little better. Late game can get a little empty, as oftentimes... When you hit end-game research, your research points feel kinda wasted,Units are divided into seperate tiers, from Tier I. to Tier IV. Despite the option of veterancy, Higher tiers almost ALWAYS win over lower tiers. If you play this game... Pay VERY close attention to your tier setups, and ability setups. You can recruit heroes whom, like your leader, can get stronger as the game progresses. Typically, a naked starting hero has a lot of trouble taking down Tier II-III units. But by the time you finish developing them into whatever you intend to make em do, presuming you did a fair to good job, your heroes will trash Tier IV units. And regardless of whether or not they are in battles, they passively pick up experience as the game progresses.Combat feels kinda sluggish and jarring, but that is probably because of my personal history and the expectations other franchises have imparted upon me. It was my experience that most minor battles are better spent autoing, and sometimes it's enjoyable to watch the replay of the battle. (Especially since you can accelerate the animation speeds. Which I find myself most comfortable at x2 speed.) There is a certain excitement factor to auto combating a closely matched engagement because of the huge gamble it represents, those also usually make the most interesting combat replays to check out.I think that covers all the major thoughts I had on gameplay, Let's move on.==================Graphics: 8 / 10Reasons for point docking.-Graphics errors that have occured.-Some visual bug based crashes.This section is largely subjective, but I think that the game delivers exactly what it tries to in graphics for the most part. I had some visual glitches here and there, most prominant of which, was a persistant rapid graphic flicker. Creating effects that weren't there, blacking out things that were supposed to be there. Usually these resolved with a game restart. It has only happened a handful of times, and could very easily be an isolated bug to my computer, I cannot be sure.==================Functionality: 7 / 10Reasons for point docking.-Visual Bug Crashes-Lategame/Veterancy Issues.-Simultanous Turn mode is less than satisfactory.I applaud the inclusing of the game manual as a button inside the game that opens an in-game manual to reference and its great detail.Simultanous turns is an awful idea when your engine will only take one global command execution at a time. All players should be able to act simultanously and not on a first come first serve basis. I presume the big hang up here is battles, but it should've been simple to think of creating a holding pattern for battles.The concept preservation score is a reflection of how I felt the dev team did on delivering us a true sequal; Scored based on keeping/improving concepts of the orginals. I will elaborate further in comments, if I can. I am at the limit sadly. I would be glad to answer questions via messages."
