76561197970038765,Recommended,226840,9814041,"Posted: 14 April, 2014",all,Pong,fun times.
,Recommended,226840,9815200,"Posted: 14 April, 2014",all,nisavid,"In this game, the main premise is a large scale rivalry between powerful mages with varying specializations and studies, who bend cities by their will toward good, evil, or whatever.Gameplay is reminiscent mostly of Heroes of Might and Magic, in a good way.  This is a 4X game with an especially strong emphasis on exploration and extermination, with heroes who go questing, conquering, leveling up, and looting for themselves and their empire.  Campaign actions are made on a high-level campaign map.  Battles play out on a lower-level map in a tactical turn-based manner, taking into account the terrain and structures of the tile on the campaign map.  Both maps use hexagonal tiles.  Armies (unit stacks) are composed of up to six units.  In a battle, all adjacent armies participate.  In some ways, this approach to combat feels like a middle ground between Civilization and Total War.Much of the design is reminiscent of Master of Magic.  Cities and units vary according to the class of the player and the race of the inhabitants.  There are six classes (arch druid, dreadnought, rogue, sorceror, theocrat, and warlord) and six races (high elf, human, orc, goblin, dwarf, and draconian).  The variety is good but not dizzying, with a solid array of standard unit types and a handful of specialists available in any city that has the requisite buildings.  Spellcasting plays a major role on the campaign map and in battles.  The spells span a wide spectrum from an assortment that is modest in cost and effect to the immensely powerful and expensive high tier.  Each school of magic (among air, earth, fire, water, creation, and destruction) is distinct, with its own characteristic effects and strategies.  The interplay between questing, empire building, warfare, and spellcasting is fun, engaging, and balanced.Compared to other 4X games, there is a diminished emphasis on exploitation.  Rather, the exploitation here is ultimately focused on serving the exploration and extermination.  You won't find options for cultural, diplomatic, or economic victories here, and the gameplay options are limited likewise.  This is not a game of peace.  [edit: Interestingly, Triumph has hinted that this is an area that they will expand in upcoming updates.]The overall fit and finish is very good, although not without room for improvement.  The UI is strongly reminiscent of Civilization V—a good choice of inspiration.  Some aspects live up to this standard better than others.  There is a Tome of Wonders (akin to Civilopedia), but it's a pain to navigate (no back button?!  among other problems), and some of its pages neglect important information.  Some stats show breakdowns on hover, as they should, but some breakdowns lack desirable detail, while others are simply omitted.  I'm curious to see if any of this improves with ongoing updates.Unlike Civilization and most other games in the 4X genre, a game of Age of Wonders III at normal pace is significantly shorter.  Expect a commitment of three to six afternoons instead of three to six full days.  Considering the pesky existence of real life, this is a very desirable trait.If you like 4X and high fantasy, and you'd like a game that combines the two in a form that's easy to swallow, then this is a great choice."
,Recommended,226840,9867012,"Posted: 18 April, 2014",all,"""the"" Chase","Just Another Review.Well so I bought this game because everyone who has played a kings bounty, disciples, heroes of might and magic?, civ and etc type of turn based strategy game will get the itch to play another if they discover they like it.Ive put around 20-30 hours into this game single player only (commonwealth) and I was pleasently suprised. After I wrapped around the controls which for whatever reason seemed backwards (left and right mouse buttons would be vise versa if i made things lol), I got pretty into the game and keep coming back. Although I could say a lot more, I am going to summarize things in bullet form as best i can and I will likely miss some things:Thinks I think that could be improved:-The research tree is still rather baffling if you want to plan ahead or unlock certain things unless you have played a lot. If it was set up like in civilization with some kind of flow chart it would be a lot easier to prioritize.-Combat animations are kinda crumby with the units (i'm just whining nothing that harms the game)-The hero cannot die clause. Warcraft 2 all over again. In the campaign you basically just keep your hero in the back away from harm and cast spells unless you want him focus'ed by the AI and to reload your save. Personally I think the hero's need more durability else they essentially just play a support role for most of the fight, cuz when they die everything stops. You aren't going to siege a city without those wonderful buffs they give all the units in the army pack nor will you go and explore ruins/want to fight if a hero isn't milking exp.-The exp system, it should essentially award everyone in the army attacking or not. Win a battle: gain most exp, lose a battle: hero gets some exp everyone else is dead lol, Run from a battle get no exp (since running could be abused). I essentially just have hero use a ranged ability to kill off whatever i can (safely) as to net more exp.-The AI during sieges, if you have 2 trebuchets you can basically funnel all the enemies through a narrow hole in the wall, ive beat a few ""very likely defeat"" situations abusing this with a very small army. If the enemy is more numerous then you past a certain extent they should just bum rush you out the gates and cut u off instead of hole up and get picked off.-Spellcasting seems kind of wonky, losing your hero for casting oil skin almost doesnt seem worth it... some spells should perhaps count as your cast and not your hero turn and the more powerful will take both...Things I dont understand yet....:-I still have no idea the use of teraforming whatsoever. Ive never encountered any situation where i would want to change my land type. Nor have unhappy people, nor really see any issues being good/evil.-Why we have so many damn resources, gold is fine for the most part, but mana crystals im always swimming in them early on and for the rest of the scenario.Things that shine:-Battles are really fun when in the open areas with a lot of obstacles around.-The unique units are quite diverse so far from what i see-Game isn't the prettiest but I really like the looks of everything-campaign is enjoyable and each level takes a fair bit of time to complete thoroughly and im just playing on easy mode to speed through~ u get a lot of playtime in this game!-The voice acting is quite good, I love the intro dialogues they are read very very well.If you want my comments on anything be sure to post and ask ill give my 2 cents.Hope this is useful lol"
