76561198052394936,Recommended,226840,19834394,"Posted: 21 December, 2015",all,Wanderlust,"In an age of expensive, flashy, superficial games, here is one that stands apart.I never played AoW2, but I played the original and it's one of my favorite classic games, right up there with Age of Empires: Age of Kings, and AoW3 is true to its roots.Newer games tend to shed the characteristics that made their predecessors great in favor of aspects that make good trailers and build extraordinary hype, only to fall flat on release when everybody finds out how shallow they are. Not this one. AoW3 delivers a deep experience that you can approach from a number of different ways: there's campaigns, scenarios, multiplayer--and random map, which is by far the best feature.For The Elder Scrolls II: Daggerfall, Bethesda randomly generated a world the size of Great Britain. Once. AoW3 does that every time you start a new random map. Yeah, they're not really comparable, but the point is made. No two random maps are the same. A single, 8-player, extra large random map will get you your money's worth out of AoW3, then you'll start a new one as a different race, different class, different school of magic, and you'll do it again and it'll be all-new. You'd better quit reading reviews and get started."
