76561198055451621,Recommended,226840,9757136,"Posted: 7 April, 2014",all,KananTheViking,"The strategic level plays very simialr to Civilization games, with considerably less managment involved, with more focus on exploring and fighting than diplomacy. Fighting is the centerpiece of the game with all the myriad units filling thier own niche. The different races have rosters of simialr core units, but each one puts some different twists, either stat or ability wise, such as goblin infantry being the cheapest but having the lowest hitpoints, or orc archers causing bleeding damage and so on. The additon of all sorts of spells across the different classes always makes combat more interesting from chain lightning to cherubs you can usually zap, burn, blast, heal, shield something in the fights.It is a good thing the combat is so interesting though as the strategic level mainly serves as a conduit and context for the turn-based battles, the only way to win is to defeat your enemies, you can form alliances and there is a diplomacy system with dispositions and item and city gifting, but the end goal is usaually either kill everyone, or make a few friends, and kill everyone else.The one sorta exception to that is the independents (minor non-player or cpu factions). These will often be something not found in the normal factions, like giants or faeires or skeletons, and if you can ally with them they will give you a quest, usally involving killing something, and then after 1-3 of these will join your faction, allwoing you to recruit the special units. Of course you could always just kill them and absorbt thier dwellings, effectively accomplishin the same thing.All in all, game is a lot of fun with a lot of replayability, it seems to  trade strategic depth on the imperial level for very high quality on the turn-based battles."
