,Recommended,226840,31783425,Posted: 16 May,all,SlamifiedBuddafied,"Age of Wonders III isn't a bad game by any means, but serves more a niche audience in the PC community. However, it serves that audience well. Not much has changed from the previous installment in terms of overall combat, which keeps a familiar feeling about the game through the lens of improved graphics. Combat is about the same, as said, but feels sharpened to a finer point and feels fairly intuitive. Though mastering combat, especially when the odds are overwhelming, means taking advantage of cover, range, terrain and the such.The story isn't anything particularly special and honestly, so far, somewhat forgettable. I can't say whether or not we're here strictly for the story, whereas the gameplay is the biggest experience I find myself coming for, as there are few games which have such playstles in such a manner. This keeps Age of Wonders III almost something of a gem, but not quite, as the combat, though fun at times, can quickly become the same old grind through armies and more so the grind of time itself. Though I think I'll chalk that up as forgivable considering the niche this game nicely fills.Gameplay wise, Age of Wonders always felt like a linear version of Heroes of Might and Magic. So if you're familiar with that series, Age of Wonders won't be a major farcry in terms of any learning curve. So being a grid based map, similar to the Civilization games map style and is turned based for city production and unit movement. Combat isn't to difficult to figure out in terms of numbers and there are plenty of info panels to help you along the way when deciding what course of action to take, without ever clouding up the screen with too much information. As said before, intuitive gameplay that's simple to figure out, but takes some time to really master.As for the technical side, I'm sure just about anyone with a rig so far back as seven years old, if not older, should be able to run this game no problem. It's hardly demanding and looks good doing what it does.I had some fun with Age of Wonders III, but I wouldn't say I'd come running back for more. But it's nice to pop in once and awhile and have some fun in this turn based RPG like fantasy game. Is it worth $30(USD)? Depends on your taste in games, but if this is something that's not in your usual cup of tea, hold out for possible sale."
