76561198006545785,Recommended,226840,16528144,"Posted: 19 June, 2015",all,Rococho Ranger,"Great game.  I got this on release and have clocked a lot of hours on it, but I waited to recommend it.I waited because it had a few balance and playability issues otu of the box, which have been adressed with patches and the Dev's listening to the community.Pros- Good division between the classes and races, everyone is good at, and weak at, something.  This makes the choice meaningful.- A style which is both functional and cool looking.- Excellent in-game encyclopedia, much refined over the patches.  Likely inspired by Civ, but not a bad inspiration at that.- Excellent tooltips. Every unit has all its abilities and current stats available at a click, no searching through menus or having to remember who does what.  This lets you focus on stratagy, and not memory tests.- Unit models. Personally I love how there is a version of each class unit for every race, they didn't skimp out on the design budget by making generic models.  Also, Goblin Angels!Cons-The campaigns are not the greatest feats of storytelling. But they do give a good vehicle for the stratagy, and a reason for the objectives.- The first expansion campaign (I haven't played Eternal Lords yet) was frustrating because it was basically a long tutorial for the new features, when I would rather have had all those new features through the campaign.  Except possibly the seals, which make sense at the point they are at (I'm not giving any spoilers here!)- There doesn't seem to be much rhyme or reason to how nuetral factions act towards you.  This may be addressed with the proposed changes to races in Eternal Lords.- The randomly generated maps do produce some wierd anomalies from time to time, but I believe these are being refined.Over all, this game deserves its 80% approval rating, and I heartily recommend it to both fans of the series and other turn-bases stratagy or empire building fans."
