,Recommended,226840,9716017,"Posted: 3 April, 2014",all,Dr Bright,"Ok...before I begin, I must say that AoW3 is my first foray into the age of wonders series.The closest equivilent game I have played is Fallen Enchantress.That said, on with the show.The game starts off with good veriaty and a beautiful visual.  You can pick from 6 races with 6 classes for each, each one a little different.  You also get the opportunity to make your own leader using any of the races as a template, each with a modifiable look and modifiable name.The gameplay of the game is fun.  As well as your fellow leaders running around, there is the independents, which are all the non-aligned units, ranging from monsters and bandits, to neutral towns that you can either conquer/annihilate for the lulz or convince to join your empire by paying them gold.  Doing this is quite fun despite the ease to simply buy up the cities and also allows you to, with patience to get access to ALL the races for yourcurrent class...or you can be a evil bugger and forcibly migrate your race to these cities.This brings me to my first little niggle regarding the AI.  The AI players work with you...unless you do things that♥♥♥♥♥♥them off and man are they picky.They take notes of EVERYTHING you do and it doesn;t take much to upset them to the point that they will launch war after war against you.  While they will forget about these, it takes a LONG time.  In my main game, I noted how my one war against a enemy had given a -1200 rating that would last for nearly 130 turns.This also brings up a AI problem I noted regarding these, which involved me getting a war penalty despite the fact that the other guy started it.  That is a bug that needs to be looked at in the least.The next part, the combat.  This is similar to Fallen enchantress in that it is a turn based fight on a special map.  Each fight takes place between the two enemies on a hex and the units in the surrounding one.  However, again, evern on dumbest setting, the AI seems suspiciously competent, sending overwelming force against their chosen target.  There is regularly little warning of an attack, meaning you'll lose at least one city before you can get a peace treaty established, which is easy to do, surprisingly.AI players will happily take a peace treaty, regardless of how well their war is going with you.  While I welcome this given how war happy my neighbours are in my current game, it is a little boring and easy to avoid a war thats going badly.Units, research and spells are next.  Like Fallen enchantress, you get to research a series of abilities/spells and units, ranging from mounted units to the local racial units depending on what race city you have up to, the kick♥♥♥♥♥juggernort 'land-ship' which is basically a 'I Win' unit.  You also get a nice selection on hero units, the cap of which you can limit.Spells however are also pretty good, and are unique to your chosen magic abilities and your class.  They have good veriaty, many have useful impact and are fun (the dreadnoughts 'mana core' nuke is just fun and a great mifddle finger to give a enemy thats overwelming you), ranging from the terraforming abilities, in-battle attacks unique to your heroes and world improvement spells such as the dreadnoughts 'supress nature; that removes all terrein penalties.However, my biggest problem is with the story campaign.  The difficulty there is ♥♥♥♥♥♥♥♥.  Half way into the FIRST MISSION...I was swarm attacked by about 30 units out no nowhere by a enemy I hadn;t even met.  This NEEDS to be patched ASAP but is not too big a problem in the long term of thingsIn conclusion, AoW3 is a great game that sits up there with the civilization and Fallen enchantress series's.  It has some bugs but its only just been released and I have no doubt that Triumph Studioes will fix these problems and game balance issues.If you like the sid meier games and Galactic Civilization games, you'll love this game too.Final rating:  9/10It loses a point due to the unbalanced AI."
