76561198007622141,Recommended,226840,15400785,"Posted: 16 April, 2015",all,fat4eyes,"After 20 years, Master of Magic finally gets a worthy spiritual successor. If you're into turn-based strategy with a magical twist, get this game. If you loved the original Master of Magic but found several recent games that tried to recapture its (ahem) magic but end up feeling a bit off (I'm looking at you Fallen Enchantress/Warlock Master of the Arcane/Endless Legend), you will not be disappointed by Age of Wonders 3.The thing that I love most about AOW 3 that it shares with Master of Magic is that the tech tree has a lot of real gamechangers. It's not just wussy +10% attack/defense/economy improvements here, no. On one turn you're playing with cookie-cutter pike/archers/cavalry, then on the next turn you research something and suddenly you have FLOATING ELDRITCH HORRORS FROM ANOTHER DIMENSION that can mind-control your enemies and panic the puny mortals that dare attack them. Or you level up your hero and suddenly YOUR ENTIRE UNIT STACK IS NOW INVISIBLE TO THE ENEMY.You don't win battles just because your attack/defense numbers are better than the enemy. You win battles by casting a spell that makes half of the enemy army run away in panic, sending in succubi to seduce the half that remained to fight for you, then use your new mind-controlled minions to kill their former allies. If you're going to play a 4X game set in a magical world, you don't want the game to just replace artillery with fireballs, rifles with bows and tanks with steampunk tanks, you want to see all the craziness that is possible in a magical world. This AOW 3 delivers really, really well."
,Not Recommended,226840,21652661,"Posted: 5 March, 2016",all,King Arthur / Dalewyn,"Let me preface this by saying I love the Age of Wonders series. I played AOW1, AOW2, and AOW:SM atonback when I was a kid. I am not writing a negative review lightly.I guess I will start off with what AOW3 did right:Continuation of the Age of Wonders story and a revival of the franchise.Nostalgic musical score consisting of AOW1 remixes. I'm not sure if I heard any AOW2/SM music though.Vassal cities. Not having to manually manage my less-important cities is really nice, and it gives another layer of diplomacy besides player-to-player....I'm supposed to write more, right? ...Right?No seriously, that's the extent of what I can consider as good in AOW3. What I listed is self-explanatory, so I will move on to the meat of this review.What I found AOW3 did wrong; why it doesn't feel like Age of Wonders:The absence of trademark spells like Enchant Weapon and Blessing (no not the in-combat only Blessing AOW3 has).The absence of heroes like Winger and Ham, heroes that were present in all three of the previous AOW games.Ripping off Civilization in GUI layout and general gameplay. ""Empire upgrades"", you mean technology? And whatever happened to researching spells that lookedanddid amazing stuff?! Hellfire from AOW2/SM, where is it?!Lack of unit and building depth. Archers are king, cities are ""finished"" when in AOW1/2/SM we would still be in earlygame. Domains are nerfed and cannot overlap each other, they are not so much ""magical sphere of influence"" as they are borders like in Civ; see below.Very shallow leader/hero design. Unlike the previous games I am finding a problem what I should be doing with my leader and heroes. The leader can't do♥♥♥♥♥♥sitting in town like before in AOW2/SM, and the leader being nerfed like such compared to the wizards in AOW2/SM means the heroes are also nerfed in their utility. Unlike AOW1, their presence isn't all that large either; forget mowing down entire armies singlehandedly, not happening here.Straight off, AOW3 does not feel like a continuation of Age of Wonders 1, 2, and Shadow Magic. Trademark spells and heroes are missing, the way the game flows is changed to be more in the venue of Civ. Honestly, I think AOW3 is more Civilization 5 with a fantasy reskin than Age of Wonders revived.AOW3 lost the unique identity that AOW1/2/SM managed to create, I don't feel that AOW3 distinguishes itself enough from the other strategy games (4X strategy in particular) in the industry like AOW1/2/SM did. If someone told me AOW3 was a Civ5 fantasy mod, I would believe them.What I found AOW3 did wrong; the technical faults:Terrible graphics. There, I said it. Compared to other games of the same genre like Civilization, the graphics arehorrible. The image simply isn't sharp, aliasing is everywhere even with anti-aliasing enabled. It feels like I'm playing the game in a smaller resolution than my monitor's native resolution, even though I am not. All the models are also ridiculously low-poly and the textures low-res by today's standards, and I have the options set on high! (I can run ultra with a minor FPS drop, but I don't see any improvement.)Clunky tactical combat. The combat in AOW1/2/SM was one of the highlights of the series. Battles werefunandexciting, especially siege battles involving cities. Casting Hellfire and seeing the city furiously burn wasamazing. Not here. Sieges just feel like a chore, and field battles are dominated by archers. Melee units are just meatshield fodder. I find myself preferring auto combat over manual combat. This is Age of Wonders, why does the combat feel so unappealing?!The revamped alignment system. Why in the seven wizards of the cosmos am I ""evil"" for migrating to my preferred races? For plundering and razing cities? For killing independent guards?Noneof these acts were even remotely ""evil"" before on a global level. In fact migrations were strongly encouraged regardless if you were playing a ""good"" wizard. I see little sense in the way the alignment system was revamped and implemented.Halflings as DLC simply rubs me the wrong way. Halflings were one of the mainstays in the series, and they were axed in the base AOW3 release before seeing a DLC release. Really? I might have gotten it still if the game was enjoyable, but I'm having doubts as this review might suggest.All in all, I am seriously saddened that I just can't bring myself to recommend this game. I really wanted to write a positive review, I adored the Age of Wonders series! Unfortunately, as a loving fan I just cannot bring myself to lie and upvote. If you have never played any of the old Age of Wonders games then you might be able to enjoy this game, but  as a long-time fan I was sorely disappointed."
