,Recommended,226840,32752376,Posted: 24 June,all,Patriarch,"So, allot of people think this is a 4x game. It's not. It's a TBS. Its like a TBS Total War - which are not 4x. Civilization is a 4x. A typical 4x, contrary to the opinion of the psychopaths who can tolerate that pointless genre, is basically just a trading simulator with the occasional pretense of combat. AoW is not a trading simulator, and it focuses on TBS combat.However, AoW does take the empire building mechanics from 4x games. But, rather than use your empire - for no apparent reason - to the exlusive end of expanding it's borders, AoW utilizes your empire to build an army. You, through extensive strategy, you beat other people's armies. To expand your borders. Ok, that's fair.It might sound like this would take away from the 4x element of gameplay, but the fact of the matter is, 4x games are so simplistic that a ♥♥♥♥♥♥♥♥ prawn could design one while dieing of aids. Thus, nothing of importance is lost; infact, I would say AoW's approach is a dramatic improvement over all 4x themed games, since AoW removes so much of the irrelevancies which are hallmarks of the genre.There are two main layers of strategic gaming: the world-map, and the combat map. On the world map, you move your armies around, manage your towns' production of infrastructure and armies, build strategic positions, alter terrain to favor your army, etc; all the geostrategy you'd expect of a mid-evil age war. Interestingly, if someone attacks an army which is stationed inside a walled city, that wall becomes part of the battleground - a massive strategic bonus. On the combat map, you do normal TBS stuff.There are a few factors, which you choose from, which determine the nature of your empire. Race, class, specializations. Each factor gives you access to different units, spells, etc, that all influence your playstyle. Though an ultimately simplistic game, it has allot of slight nuance that can change the course of a fight, which can change the course of the overall war. Still, solid gameplay and strategy.Downside: the developers still haven't figured out how to stream-line the game. For example, you have to watch units move during TBS phase. You can speed them up, sure, but why the hell do I need to watch them move? I'm playing a strategy game; why do you think I'm that stupid? And as much as I enjoy watching my units attack three times, it still wastes time. I do strategy. I do thinking good. I don't need to see the animations to understand the end result. Just give me an option to turn it off, it's that simple.The TBS camera is a joke too, though I haven't made an effort to turn off it's automated movements."
