76561197984138185,Recommended,226840,15371216,"Posted: 14 April, 2015",all,Zindaras,"Age of Wonders III perfects the Age of Wonders formula, and it is an easy recommendation for anyone who's enjoyed the previous games. For those who did not, it's a very good game to get into the series with. At the start of the game, you pick a race and a class for your leader. Your class affects your game very deeply, as each class has access to different spells, different units, and different upgrades that determine your playstyle. Race matters a little bit less, but there are a lot of neat interactions between the various units: the goblins, for example, all have a poison theme, with some inflicting a debuff on their victims that make them weaker to poison damage. With your units and your hero, who gains experience and learns new tricks, you then walk around the world map and enter treasure sites or fight opponents. The tactical battles are great fun, and the massive importance of the flanking mechanic means that good play is rewarded.There are a few points of crticism, however. The campaign is nice, but hasn't really progressed beyond the original's idea of a number of scenarios connected by sheets of text. There are a few scenarios that are really different, and I enjoyed those greatly, but the majority of the campaign felt samey. The biggest point of criticism to the game, however, is the late game. The late game is boring and lacks variety: you're fighting huge battles with only end-tier units (because anything lower would take away important space in your army), so all the cute interactions you get at the start of the game are taken away, as you just mix and mash whatever Tier III or IV units you build, because that just works better. Because every class only has access to one Tier IV unit and two Tier III's, and each race gives you one Tier III unit (which all fill the exact same role), this means that you're basically using 4 units at the end. The battles then become overly long and don't feel as if they reward skill as much as the early-game battles.There's one question that every TBS-game needs to be asked to see whether it's good or not: do you want to play another turn? Since AoW III answers that question with a yes, even in the later stages in the game that I don't enjoy so much, the game gets a solid recommendation from me.Note: this review is for the original game. I will update the review as I buy and play the DLC.Edit: See my review of the Golden Realms for my full thoughts on that DLC, but I think it is a fantastic addition to the game and an absolute must-have. It makes the base game so much more enjoyable, you really don't want to go without it."
76561198047005019,Recommended,226840,13103761,"Posted: 27 November, 2014",all,AndrewDavid1992,"Age of wonders was a great joy of my younger years.I was pleasantly surprised to see a new installment in the franchise and decided to dive right in.Everything from before is fantastically revitalized and remodeled, if only a little basic on the animation side; it quickly makes up for it with a broad scope of customization and fantastically well executed strategical elements.Fans of the fire emblem series will be also be joyously engrossed in similar feelings as they try to keep their favoured units in play, while deeply engrossed in the sheer magnitude of the leader skill tree and stat progression.one of my new favourites; Highly recommended."
76561198031273221,Recommended,226840,13945284,"Posted: 11 January, 2015",all,Sheepscuit,"First of all I'm 50/50 whether to vote up or down for this game.Positives -Overall it's a great looking game.Multiple races add diversityDifferent leader types (Theocrat/Warlord for eg) gives even more diversityHuge range of skills to use in battleUpgrade-able/Leveling up Heroes/LeadersNice, smooth feel to the game play.Battles are fun, with lots of strategy.Negative -This is where I fall out with the game now. I cannot really play it as I want to. I respect and understand now that it's a different type of game than I thought/wanted it to be and these issues are really my own.Simply put the game is NOT an empire builder of any kind.I'm used to the Civ games where I would build/enhance a small empire with all the technology/culture/buildings and then start to spread with superior firepower and bonuses, assimilating one city at a time from the enemy to my empire.Here however, it is much more of a constant, aggressive battle tactic game. Doing my usual tactic, I can research all the stuff, upgrade my cities fully, and yet only be able to produce Tier 3 units. By this point the enemy factions randomly declare war for no reason and are sending wave after wave of Tier 4 units (and really I've only had the chance to build Tier 1/2s and I struggle to change focus and build enough Tier 3 to hold them off.Another slight disappointment is that cities have no defence, if there's no army garrisoned, not even a siege option such as Civ has. So losing cities is VERY easy to do against the higher Tier armies you face.Now as I say, this is mostly just the type of game it is, more akin to the Total War series than Civ.I have tried multiple tactics within my usual play style and none have worked for me yet. So I've put the game down for now, maybe I'll try again in the future.Conclusion -I do recommend this game because of the general quality of it.TL:DR -Buy if you want aggressive, tactical and constant combat.Avoid if you want an Empire Builder with military aspects."
