,Recommended,226840,15814749,"Posted: 13 May, 2015",all,PurpleXVI,"By and large a solid successor to the Age of Wonders series. The combat's been cleaned up to be even more fun, the visuals are nicer, the mechanics more enjoyable and the calculations behind the results more visible, making it far easier to tell what to do to improve your odds and worsen your enemy's. Also features better enemy AI, in my opinion.About the only downside is that a lot of campaign time involves you hauling around sub-heroes that aren't allowed to die, but it's a minor annoyance. You CAN keep them alive, but sometimes you get pinned into situations where all you can do is either cheat, repeatedly reload autosaves hoping for a lucky break OR skip back several turns to your last manual save so you didn't maneuver one of them into an unsaveable situation.It also feels like the spellbook is a lot slimmer for each class(but also like leader class actually matters a lot more this time around, heroes are another system that's vastly improved). I found myself casting spells a lot less than during Shadow Magic... but on the other hand I also found a lot less battles decided by who had the Casting Points left over to spam ""affects all enemies""-spells.Mostly the game feels at a bit of a shortage for ""mid-range"" spells. That is, spells that aren't as battle-changing as Mass Panic, Smoke Screen or the druid's beast summoning, but still have more effect than just outright attacking with your leader(or having them use an ability like Convert or such). At the moment it feels like most of the spells are either AT the level of just attacking/using an ability or they're huge battlefield-affecting stuff.Still, overall, I'd say the game's an improvement on Shadow Magic, which my impression is that most people consider to be the apex of Age of Wonders so far. The expansions are also nice additions.And of course the soundtrack is just to die for. I absolutely love it.Only thing I have absolute criticism for is the voice-overs between campaign missions. They're just not very well done, though the writing's fine."
