76561198021852773,Recommended,226840,14944163,"Posted: 18 March, 2015",all,mecklenberg,"How do you know when a game has surpassed its predeccessors? I believe it's at the moment that you start to think of the current version, rather than its predecessors, as definitive of the series.With update 1.5 (still beta as it is) AOWIII has now reached that stage.Let me give you an example.I am a sorceror-dwarf playing on the far right of the map, and peaceful with my immediate neighbors.  Voraditius the Theocrat is on the far left and quickly disposes of his Orc-Warlord neighbour, then declares war on me. This is at about turn 60, so both sides have top-level units available. We both decide - that's the correct expression, I'm sure -  to conduct reconnaissances in force on each other's territory.  I drop a couple of Horrors into my defending stack and see his raiders off handily. It's what happens at the other end of the map that is so brilliant. Bear in mind that I'm adding a Horror to my invaders each other turn, or a erpent each turn If I run low on troops, plus various gold conventional troops totalling two stacks. at the outset.Voraditius plays like Napoleon.Attack his towns? Those anaemic looking defennders turn out to be backed up with the power of Shrine of Animation, which brings back my own troops as undead on his team. Ignominious defeat.Probe for weaknesses? He concentrates his stacks with diabolical ingenuity and sends me packing with heavy losses.I send another hero with a stack of Naga units. Same thing happens - Immobilisation is killing me. Eventually I have to rethink and send the right units and heroes to tackle the Napocrat and his omnipotent Shrines of Smiting.It helps to sac units to distract his armies to positions where they can be picked off. I'm also sending futher troops (giants and siege equipment to tackle the walls, which I should probably have done at the start). I catch Voraditius the little Corsican in the open and send him to the void for a couple of turns, during which I can run riot, Black Prince style. At last we face other in a huge Waterloo-type battle where I have only 3 units left at the end. Voraditius capitulates. Pure Turing - no way of telling he was 'just' an AI opponent.Only one issue; Another opponent kept declaring war on Voraditius even after he was defeated. Entirely understandable, but a little strange.All this in simple a random scenario. Ten thumbs up - a new classic is born."
