76561198028682072,Recommended,226840,15804384,"Posted: 12 May, 2015",all,Quakernuts,"Have you ever thought that Civilization needed more personality than some pompous know it all from the annals of history strutting around on a horse or something?  Well look no farther as we delve into a world filled with magical creatures such as Dragons, Griffins, Goblins, Orcs, and Succubi...Sweet sweet succubi...Ahem...where was I?Oh yes, the game!  A turn based strategy that does it's best to capture the feel of Civilization with a couple of added bonuses.  Whenever you get into a battle, you end up in a turn based battle scenario with each of your units crying for attention and wanting to kick some♥♥♥♥♥  While it may seem like a standard ""Click unit, click enemy, repeat"" type of battle method, there are subtle nuances that keep everything in check.  Such as positioning, obstruction for arrows and spells, morale and overall health of a unit that affects their damage output as the battle progresses.  Each race has their own racial bonuses to add to the pile, couple that with your class as well and you have a ton of possibilities as to how your units will fare depending on a situation.  There's enough choice and consequence here to make each game unique.Speaking of units, let's talk about the big one.  Your hero, head honcho, leader, dictator and ruler of the overworld.  A custom created character (Or pre-made cause you're boring and no one likes you) that can and probably should be your most powerful unit late game.  They are just one of many heroes that you can hire and use to lead your armies, although your hero has the benefit of respawning after several turns if they are killed, unlike hired heroes.There are a few gripes, such as the low singular army count, as in you can only have 5 units in one army meaning that no battle feels as big as it should without several individual armies backing you up.  The game, at least for me, has a tendency to be bogged down with latency issues.  Clicking and waiting several seconds for the character to pick up on the fact that I'm smacking his or her head in a general direction.  Also, my biggest complaint about the game has to be the multiplayer matchmaking using a P2P (Peer to Peer) network model that requires individual computers to connect to each other.  Understandable from a business perspective, allowing them to shirk off having to run servers, but painfully obnoxious when it comes to the layman just trying to get together with his buds and having to literally turn off his firewall just to connect to anyone.Virus's ho, right?All in all though, the game is generally fun to play if somewhat slower paced than many people are probably hoping for.  The customization of units and the leader of your faction lends to it some sense of personality and attachment as your Orc Dreadnought leads several landships into battle. If you are playing single player, then the mutliplayer connection issues are non-existent.  The latency issues might rear their head even in single play, but being that it's turn based isn't too much of a problem.If you liked turn based games with RPG mechanics mixed in, you'll like AoW III."
