76561198080704716,Recommended,226840,12176476,"Posted: 21 September, 2014",all,dhammer_911,"This game is very entertaining. I am mainly writing to respond to criticisms that the game lacks depth, which initially made me hestitant about the game. The sale price of 19.99 USD tipped the scales in favor of the game (I was also considering Solar Empire and Endless Space). I'm glad the sale was going on because so far this is a great purchase. For a pure 4x game, I could see a lack of depth. However, this game is a hybrid between a 4x and RPG. I find RPGs too shallow to hold my interest, but the RPG elements here add a facet to this game that I haven't seen in other 4x games. The fact that it's unique makes it interesting. True...the research tree is anemic, but I have a lot of fun learning the spells, which have a fresh and dynamic affect on every aspect of the gaming experience. But to me, the RPG-style battle engine is what takes this to the next level. It is somewhat complex and very engaging, and mixed with more traditional 4x aspects, AOW III provides a nice experience that has kept my interest through that crucial first 24 hours. It also helps that the gameplay is smooth and intuitive, and the graphics are beautiful. So far, this is my favorite purchase since Civ V. One note is that I did have a crash. However, this was after a 14-hour session."
76561197970968073,Recommended,226840,12180678,"Posted: 21 September, 2014",all,Roboman,"Just got this game and I don't know who made what first but this is my first time playing a game in the AoW franchise and found it's pretty much the same game as HoMM, although... it's fun. HoMM failed on the fun part their last couple installments and this game delivers. It's a good time. Not to blow my own horn but I think the AI is pretty weak in this, I tried normal difficulty and it was a joke, then 1 up from normal and it still wasn't much of a challlenge. AI would declare war on me, I'd wipe him out without breaking a sweat, I'd try to make peace with the next guy, nope he wants war... he's dead too, etc.Having individual troops in your army rather than stacks of troops like in HoMM is a big improvement. You get more of a feel for how tough your guys are rather than having to always check how big the stack is and do some mental math. Your magic will be strong but not broken and so far I've played 2 classes (Warlord and Sorcerer) and the style of play changes quite a lot so it adds some variety. You get to cast spells both in combat and in the global map and the global spells / disjuction side of the game is very relevant. In combat, your hero can be strong but not that relevant as a fighting unit lategame, but  you'll have spells that make massive impact.As with most TBS games, at the end of the turn the AI helps you control your stuff by prompting you to confirm your orders for your units or give orders to units with none (of course it won't bother you if you ""Garrison"" the units). But it's kinda reduntant, if I give a unit a move order that takes 5 turns to complete, it won't just automove every turn, it will prompt me to confirm his journey for the next 5 turns. Kinda pointless. Another thing I'd like is to be able to have a town governor or something to build my cities up for me without me having to bother with microing it. Late game, I just wanna manage my armies, not click through the repetative build orders of my 20-30 city empire. I would also like a minister of defence or something so he could worry about  sending my troops out to defend my cities, let me pick what goes in the garrison of border cities  and safe zone cities but don't make me do it myself. hehe. Also the builder unit could use some automation, ""go around and make roads to connect my cities"" seems a boring task I shouldn't have to micro myself.Okay enough ranting about my pet peeves, overall the game is great and a welcome addition to the turn based strategy genre.I recommend buying if you like this style of game, there's not many out there that are more fun."
