76561198001269905,Not Recommended,226840,9899247,"Posted: 22 April, 2014",all,[TG] Maligner,"I had hopes for this game and did some homework on it to try to determine if it was worth paying full retail, and turns out it isn't.Graphically the game looks fine. I'm not one to gush about graphics; gameplay is king for me. The game also seemed to run o.k.The main issue I seem to be having is the tactical combat. Just a few niggly bits jump out immediately and, frankly, I don't want to keep playing. This is quite disappointing.You start combats just a few steps from the edge of the map, making tactical retreats nearly impossible. Pretty much every engagement is only a simple turn or two away from melee. This nearly nullifies missile unit's tactical options. Since you are fairly limited on number of units to begin with, this is pretty major.Balance seems off. As an example, I ganged up on an assasin unit that is seen in the second battle of the starter campaign. I whittled the unit down to a single health point of 36 (1/36). Next turn, the unit assassinated my hero, and the game was over. Second turn into an easy game. I can see this being a selling point for many but turns out that you should be managing unique saves of every turn unless you want to replay the last several turns since the last save every time some game balance issue results in the end of the game.Why not just use the auto save? Because during the same game, I had a full stack placed on my second town and my main army was marching. Suddenly a two stack attack landed on my town. Defeat, with the death of a hero that must survive. Game over on easy for the second time in 30 minutes. Auto save has my other army more than a turn away and unable to help. So, I must revert to a previous save and replay several battles and tutorial elements.The game is o.k., or would be if it was priced like and indie title at about $10 or $15. But for $40 I don't think the balance is there. Perhaps some of my concerns will be addressed. Perhaps it's just not for me. Either way, I felt compelled to share my thoughts."
