76561198013132245,Recommended,226840,15827077,"Posted: 14 May, 2015",all,huminado,"Every time I play this I have fun.Also I just made a 5 level map with protected areas and one way portals.  Here aremy maps.AI Improvements:And now the AI seems to be smart enough to handle that map without drooling like an embecile!  I think this is great - because now I can continue work on that map and make it what I had envisioned in the first place, or close to it at least.The big drawback to most randomly generated maps is that once an area is ""cleaned up"" it remains mostly dormant.  So that is somewhat mitigated with the map I'm working on.Because the AI has improved, I can seriously consider getting the other DLC I was holding back on.Atmosphere:Atmospherically, this game is possibly THE BEST LOOKING FANTASY 4X OF ALL TIME.  Go ahead, just try going into the editor to create your own map.  It's like spending time painting a picture - very relaxing way to spend time and it's productive and fun to make an atmosphere people might enjoy.Other than the board, the UI is very nice.  I guess I don't really notice when a UI is nice - I only notice when it's deplorable - and this one is artful and it's clear a lot of love went into it.Hero Generation:The character generator has personality.  Really - this is the first game with a character generator (I guess I mean avatar) where I spent time with the appearance giving each one personality.  Because the range of appearances and role play are vastly beyond anything I've seen before - making a creepy witch was my favorite.Tactics:This is a great tactical mind workout playing the tactical map for each battle.  Because the maps are relatively large, interesting strategies can take place.  I don't anticipate Endless Legend will ever come close to the tactical experience AoW provides.City Building:There are maybe 6 or so different building ""paths"" to choose for a city.  So to get access to specific units you might have to build several buildings on a specific path.  These paths aren't very obvious and there's a learning / memorization (or documentation lookup) curve involved with cities.  I like it, but it might not suit everyone.Units:Units are not customizable, although heros are.  This is where Endless Legend seems to provide a vaster gameplay experience in comparison.  All units do level though, which is at least somewhat engaging to track which units are closest to leveling to prioritize who gets the kills and reap XP.Community:The modding community is very active and supportive.  I got a lot of encouragement and comments and that makes a huge game engagement difference, if you enjoy trying other people's mods or making them yourself.Missing Things Nobody Misses:There's something you can log into.  I have no idea.  I just play as guest all the time.  So it's a non-intrusive experience unlike other games.  Guess what?  That lack of ♥♥♥♥♥♥♥t commands a higher price tag and is well worth it.  [I'm looking at you HOMM.]"
