,Recommended,226840,14169006,"Posted: 25 January, 2015",all,federated state of trollnesia,"There are some huge negatives for me:-Lower tier units rapidly become useless compared to higher tiered units. Although higher tiered units require some investment to acquire, they are not much more expensive than the lower tiered units. This makes it such that the best strategies are just spamming leviathans, flame tanks, or archon titans. I don't like that. I prefer the skirmishes the early game has to offer, with lots of archers, swordsmen, and caster armies. These feel tactical and well-suited, but once players can begin to amass the higher tiered units it just becomes a race to see who can build these the most. War is then less about exploration and tactics, and more just who managed to assert a few good cities and start pumping out the stronger units. It's a classic problem for most strategy games, but here it ruins the fun for me. This problem has been solved reasonably well in the past - it's not like riflemen in Warcraft 3 suddenly went out of style even towards the end of a game, yet archers rapidly become useless in this. It's annoying.Otherwise, it's a fun turn-based game in dire need of some hard balancing (honestly, leviathans are insane since you can sumnmon them anywhere with mana and have a fear effect PLUS they can mind control units, it's not even fair if a player gets six of these up and running, which isn't hard to do if you get enough shrines)."
