76561198079020363,Recommended,226840,13452775,"Posted: 19 December, 2014",all,crickit90,"I just started. I have only completed one map, but I played for eleven hours straight because this game warrants it. Everything levels up, and as they do all sorts of upgrades occur. Many of them are automatic, but you get to customize your heros in useful ways. They give you 5 points to spend as you please. These can new passive or active bonuses including, but not exclusive to: attack up, defense up, life up, rapid regeneration, resistance up, new abilities like heal, rust, first strike, increased vision. The settlements have a simple spread, but it is deep enough for you to specialize with the bonus reasources inside of your domain. There are not many units that cannot be dealt with by tier 1 (the lowest) units if you get their experience all the way up. Archers are actually protected by the infantry you place in front of them because attacks of opportunity are present. The only real complaint I have is with the notifications system. It tells you most things twice, and in such a way that you may not know how to respond. For instance, if an enemy enters your territory you get a notification that will highlight the square the enemy entered. Unfortunately, this is not normally going to be the last square the enemy occupied, so you will need to search in up to a 12 square radius for said enemy. This is a fast paced game. If you don't overrun your enemy quickly, expect a long uphill battle."
76561198064600875,Recommended,226840,13503747,"Posted: 21 December, 2014",all,Exfilter,"This game has a great many aspects I personally enjoy, the most prominant being the ability to create the leader of your faction/ primary hero unit. With the ability to customize class, race, and skill specialization (as well as appearance, of course), AoW pulls off their mix of fantasy RPG and strategy game deftly. The 3 choices above have a real impact, given that they determine what elite units you can produce and what spells you can cast.The only weakness of the game is, sadly, its battle system. For fans of the Total War series, who will find most of this game rather easy to adapt to, the lack of ability to plan and strategize battles as well as you do diplomacy or city development can be very frustrating. One example of this is pre-battle deployment, which arranges all units in a long line, seemingly at random. One often feels slightly helpless in these battles, as the whim of the computer will sometimes place powerful ranged units with no armor in the center, in striking distance of the enemy infantry, while your infantry are placed on the end of the line, and are therefore useless for the first few turns. In essence, deployment becomes the deciding factor in many battles, and you don't control it.This is a rather gaping hole of bad design in an otherwise well put together game. Buy it if it's on sale, as the rest of the game is quite fun, but honestly if you've got enough money to pay full price just buy Endless Legend (which is better, apparently; I've never played it)TL,DR : Fun blend of strategy and fantasy RPG with a few oversights, esspecially in the battle system. Buy it if it's on sale."
,Recommended,226840,13550234,"Posted: 23 December, 2014",all,Kurp ♥,Better HOMM than what Ubisoft is capable of making.
76561197966556850,Recommended,226840,13551315,"Posted: 23 December, 2014",all,Big Dracula,"Awesome follow up to Age of Wonders: Shadow Magic that isn't content to just rehash the same old mechanics. It manages to recreate the atmosphere of the older Age of Wonders games while changing up the game is some pretty dramatic and intelligent ways. Age of Wonders III separates race and culture for units; a goblin, for example, can now be any type of class from Theocrat to Rouge. This not only adds a tremendous variety and replayability to the game, but is also a statement that race shouldn't define one's culture.Things to complain about? I get nostalgic for the awesome 2D art of the older games. All the graphics are now rendered in 3D which have less charm and sometimes makes it difficult to distinguish low and mid tier units from one another. On the battlefield, mid and low tier units are no longer individuals, but small stacks that function like individuals. As such, they are smaller and sometimes indistinguishable from one another. It's something you get used to, and since the units are as full of personality as the older games, it's ultimately a minor complaint.There are also less races to choose from than the older games, but since you now must choose both race and class, variety doesn't suffer as much as you would think. Still, the more races and classes as Triumph Studios makes available, the better. I'm personally hoping for Dark Elves and Lizardmen.This is one of the best fantasy 4X games out there; a nice balance of new and old, great music and atmosphere, and a bright future ahead of it in the way of expansions and patches."
