76561198002948133,Recommended,226840,12670791,"Posted: 28 October, 2014",all,Turjak,"AOW3 is a solid title. It can be compared roughly to Fallen Enchantress or Heroes of Might & Magic/ Kings Bounty, with a few major, major differences.There's significantly less emphasis placed on the range of options in strategic meta-game (the focus is on war, full stop) , and hero development is more of a shallow affair.However, it more than makes up for these deficiencies/differences with its combat system.Games are fast, and combat has a great deal of depth (flanking, better use of 3-D space) that you won't see in other fantasy 4x titles. The pacing is such that AOW doesn't want you waiting 20 turns between battles, but keeps them coming, turn after turn.I would recommend it to anyone who enjoys online or random map play and likes the genre, although I am really enjoying the single player campaign after I've discovered the secret to making it easier (and having more fun) is to play a breakneck pace constantly on the rush.The intial learning curve is a little steep, but once you get the hang of it, you'll enjoy playing the battles (for the most part, as large engagements are neat to see, but kind of a mess to coordinate)."
