76561198005434974,Not Recommended,226840,35057609,Posted: 18 September,all,lucern,"I am a veteran of AoW1, AoW2, and the supreme AoW: Shadow Magic, who happily spent months on each of those titles a teenager's lifetime ago.  Around that time, I so geeked out about the possibility of an AoW sequel that I thought of a whole document full of half-baked ideas and sent it to Triumph.  Lennart Sas was so nice about it.  In this light, it pains me to not recommend this title.  I don't dislike it, but I can't recommend it. It's more neutral than negative.  It boils down to utter disinterest during combat, and there's really not a game left if you don't like the combat.  That surprised me, as I used to love the previous games as well as games like Master of Magic.+ Triumph games are reasonably priced and very well supported.  How many games still get patches 3 years after release?  These aren't cash grabs in an industry full of them.+ There is a ton of variety in leaders, and the diverse gameplay of their various classes is a genuine development for this genre.+ Simultaneous turns, which I first was amazed by in AoW1, is still the gold standard in the genre.+ The graphics are colorful and illustrative of what's going on.+ Music is excellent and varied+ Between the different leader classes and features, your setup really is different between games.+ There's a lot of care put into each individual part of the game; again it just doesn't add up in a way I like.- There are tons of units, but little unit variety.  Each race has a bounty of units you should never build if you don't want to lag behind economically, and they're samey.  What's +1 here and -1 there in a game with basic HP ranges around 30?  This isn't interesting variation to me.- It feels like there's a ton of depth to the combat potentially, but it's mostly hidden away on character pages that you'd have to seriously study before making a move.  There is a log that shows you your mistakes after you make them, but it never answered my questions in a way that I could learn from.  The battles felt the same to me: having not played it in 4 months at the time of this review, I cannot remember even one single combat apart from others.- Units start too close together, or at least too close in a game that won't let you use formations.  Forming up should probably be done before you're 20 yards from the enemy.  Add to this: units start so close together that range is basically meaningless outside of a siege.  Combat ends up being about doing chintzy facing hits so that real hits can flank and/or playing a mean element resistances game.  Whee.- Heroes are diverse in theory, but in practice they are more or less their class and any lucky items you've found. This is either a clever commentary on dull MMORPGs or another lost opportunity.- You will probably never get used to the fact that enemy squads are an illusion - they just have a health total represented by the number of soldiers.  Heal 1 guy and get 6 back.- The story I'm told is good, but it happens on a big narrative dump between missions, so I have no idea.  If you can look at static art while a story is slowly narrated at you in 2017, then I admire your patience.  Keep in mind that I know all the old characters and still can't do it.- Cities have a progression, but it really just feels like a temporal one.  There aren't very interesting choices there for most classes, partly because you can't seriously build most units because of the limited space in battles; you can't waste any on a horde of low tier soldiers.- With this little of interest going on in the strategic layer, why do games like this bother with random campaign maps?  This has basically never been satisfying in tactical games.TLDR: Watch a non-steam video of the combat.  If it looks fun, give it a try: Triumph is still one of my favorite developers. I just couldn't muster an appreciation for it."
