,Recommended,226840,11271641,"Posted: 16 July, 2014",all,Whap XI,"Do NOT pay full price for this game. It is nowhere near worth the £30 asking price, but that said, it's still a good bit of mindless fun. A fairly obvious clone of parts of Civs 4 and 5, with heavy fantasy elements.The game looks gorgeous, and runs well, but is heavily lacking in depth and polish. There are some finicky ways in which you have to micro manage things. Builder units cannot have their orders queued up, so if you're building, for example, a long road, you have to give the builder the order to build a road every turn, rather than giving it to them once at the start of the road and the builder autobuilds to the end. The custom-map menu doesn't lock in your settings from use to use, and the amount of times I've forgotten to change one of about three things, and had to restart a game to change simultaneous turns (which I cannot stand, and as I've said, is the default setting which can't be changed) is ridiculous. These are just a couple of ways in which the game lacks polish.Depth, as I have mentioned, is also sorely lacking. All cities can only build the same buildings, aside from buildings coming from the racial and class bonuses of your leader. Any variation of cities only comes from the bonus improvements in the land around them. These are in the game from the beginning, and cannot be created, destroyed, or changed. You cannot build farms or any other kind of improvement as in Civ, but are limited to Watchtowers, Fortresses and roads. Roads don't give any sort of bonus, other than your units moving faster. There is no negative effect to having more cities as in Civ, where tech costs and such go up. In AoW3, having fewer cities isn't a playstyle. You want to expand as fast and as much as possible.So yeah. Lacks polish. Lacks depth. Is still a lot of mindless fun. It looks gorgeous and it works. I recommend this game, but get it on sale. It is nowhere near worth £30."
