76561198040277969,Not Recommended,226840,15409194,"Posted: 16 April, 2015",all,Marduk,"This is a beautiful character creator with an extremely deep concept... attached to a totally crap game engine. The character creator is so promising and varied it's hard not to keep going back and trying to find that ""sweet spot"" that makes the rest of the game playable, but it isn't there. This game sucks. Maybe future updates will get around to making it not suck so much but so far it's a steaming heap with one of the best character creators I've yet seen on a 4X game.It's a mediocre alternative to Fallen Enchantress, the difference being primarily that Fallen Enchantress is a playable (though not terribly fun) 4x game with low-end graphics and boring gameplay. What AoW3 brings to the table is prettier artwork... and almost nothing else, as yet.Considering it's been in a ""finished product"" state for over a year now and already has content updates, I've got little hope that it's actually going to be upgraded to a ""decent"" game at any point. It's a bad game... but again, the graphics are pretty and the character creator is top-notch.[EDIT]: I really want to love this game, I really do... I've given it a solid 80 hours of trying now, and I still can't do it. I've worked out how to stack starting conditions and faction options in a manner that allows me to eventually sometimes expand beyond my first city before getting overrun by wandering barbarian hordes... I've learned how to exploit the subterranean map for everything it's worth... I've figured out dwellings and their various diplomatic side-effects... I've even learned how to mix the various magical schools and which race/class combinations benefit more or less from several varieties of pre-game picks selections. I've also discovered now how to make use of the ""growth momentum"" meta-economic (which has no indicators, and is not apparent because there is no 'development tree' of any kind on cities, units, magic, or otherwise... it's just implied by one stage unlocking another one as you progress) and I've figured out how to use hero hiring to ""blend strategies"" for empire development......but even through all of that, the game is still... shallow like a puddle on the sidewalk. It's got no depth. City specialization boils down to placement near world-bound resources like ""dungeons"" and ""tombs"" and such. While you can do a tiny bit of terraforming, it's extremely restricted (you can change the surface mapping of a tile amongst a limited range of options based on your initial picks, you cannot raise and lower terrain and you cannot branch your empire out across multiple environs). The morale system is disappointing in a variety of ways, and makes the initial starting conditions extremely unbalancing if you do not rig the game heavily in your favor before you even begin.As a final note, the artwork is absolutely fantastic, I can't say that enough. This is probably the most beautiful 4X currently on the market... but that's all it's really got going for it. The UI is counter-intuitive, the gameplay dynamics are so biased that every game is a foregone conclusion before you even begin, and the development/progress system is literally a flatline rather than any kind of curve.The people working on this game seem to be missing a critical element from their team... it's like a bunch of art students tried to make a game none of them would ever actually play. It's got no passion, no depth, no sense of accomplishment, no actual challenge, no emotional value.It isn't a problem with the engine, it isn't a problem with the graphics. It's just a complete lack of engagement between design and implementation."
