76561198083111146,Not Recommended,226840,15581535,"Posted: 27 April, 2015",all,Wimpie,"I would not recommend this game, for singleplayer. There are a few issue's i have that cause me not to enjoy this game.Warning: this is highly subjective, based on personal experience. Therefore i recommend keeping that in mind!- First the depth.When you start the game and see all the different races and the specialisations you may get the idea that there's alot to discover. However every race play's very alike, there are differences ofcourse but the general concept is the same throughout. (swordsman, archer, pikeman, horseman etc).The specialisations do bring some variation but the research-tree's attached to them are short. The extra units for each specialisation is a welcome addition, however it's not quite enough.- Combat/balance.The combat has some meat to it, it's the focus of the game. Some interesting mechanics suchs as attacks of oportunity and hero skills add to the strategic element. But because of the low variety of units it becomes more of the same much too soon.-Pacing.The big focus in this game is as i said the combat. Sadly around turn 50-60 all units but tier 4 units get less usefull. Wichs results in tier 4 unit spam, it takes away from the already limited choise and variation. And for me that is were most of my games ended, because i did not feel like spamming one unit.- Diplomacy.Diplomacy is barebone in this game, it's about declaring war or signing a peace treaty. You can interact some more with independant city's, like vasalisation. But when you tend to wage war everyone will like you less, making it harder to have good relations with anyone (as a war decleration effects every other player/independant) it's simply the most viable mechanic by far to just wage war as the only option.- Strategic placement.This is combat related, you get to choose 6 unit's for each stack. Then you can fight with multiple stacks in one fight to up to (i believe) 48 units. This sounds very nice but there's a big problem that i personally have with it.If you fight with 2 stacks versus one the AI tends to advance towards one of them. That leaves the other to catch up since the distance between allied stacks is relatively large.Because of that the reason to fight with multiple stacks becomes less important, your main stack is gonna do most of the work (hopefully, the AI might attack the other stack).Or the AI splits it's army destroying it's chances on it's own.In encounters (versus independants roaming or placed around the map) the battlefield is so small that ranged units can reach your army in the first turn. And they get to go first because you attacked. So they get a free attack in.... does not seem very strategic.- City defense.This seems to be done by placing units within the city, wich cost upkeep. The AI will ninja your city, it even intends to do so. The only way is to use units wich should have bin fighting in your army, there should be a building for it, but none to find.-Graphics.This is done fairly well, the game does look beautifull and the animation quality is high. It also runs very well and support for the game is good, the devs are very active and helpful!All in all i expected something along the lines of Warlock or HoMM. But this is a different creature entirely. That said the issue's i have may not be a problem for others, as many people do like this game. And for good reason, i did like aspects of it very much. Sadly the points mentioned made it not so enjoyable for me personally.I would not recommend unless none of the above is an issue, if you do get it i'd recommend to wait for a sale (it happends frequently)!"
76561198172598610,Recommended,226840,34709997,Posted: 3 September,all,MeierLink,Good game.
,Not Recommended,226840,16106940,"Posted: 31 May, 2015",all,Zill,"In order to do Age of Wonders III justice, I would have to write two reviews. The tactical layer works very well. The strategic layer doesn't. Regardless of whether I recommend this game or not, I'm letting my opinion on one subsystem trump the other.The tactical layer uses a fun and flexible system that involves frequent trade offs between moving fast and being able to deal damage. It encourages you to move your units carefully and orchestrate coordinated chains of actions. Unit types are well balanced against each other so that there really is a point to using a bit of everything. The spellcasting system is somewhat less robust and clearly favours damage dealing over buffs, but still provides added depth. All of this is made even better by varied tactical maps and enemy factions. This is game design at its best.It is, sadly, wasted to some degree, because the strategic layer is a classic case of form over essence. Strategic maps are large and full of landmarks, but there are no mechanics for making all this complexity ""observable"". You just keep stumbling upon things that hide in the fog of war - or they stumble upon you, usually at the least convenient time. There's no way for you to take all the necessary precautions, so you're often at the mercy of randomness. Most scenarios make assumptions with regard to optimal play style but never tell you about them. Sometimes you're supposed to rush. Sometimes you're supposed to turtle. Sometimes you need to clear NPC nests, and sometimes they are just red herrings. There's no feedback from the game's dynamics until it's too late. It's been over 70 hours and I'm still just picking city upgrades at random.So there's one system that works, and one that doesn't. The reason why I'm going for ""not recommended"" is the storyline and setting. It's childish, naive and not at all compelling; full of cliches, and saturated with casual imperialism. You could say storylines are not important in 4X games, but then why not just make a 4X game without a story, like good old Civilization or Master of Orion? If the story is important enough to justify preceding every mission with a five-minute, three-act briefing, then it should be judged just like a proper story that it's trying do be. Age of Wonders III fails miserably in this respect.Additionally, the game does a poor job at explaining its systems to the player. There's just a huge infodump of a manual that you're supposed to read, and the visual language takes some getting used to. It took me a good few hours to sort things out on my own."
