76561197970847743,Not Recommended,226840,23368450,"Posted: 3 June, 2016",all,broncowitz,"I so much want to recommend this game.  The first turn based strategy game I played was Warlords.  And later I became obsessed with Heros of Might and Magic.  Age of Wonders III is like Warlords and Heros mated and had a beautiful new baby.  I loved it at first.  The UI looks good and is pretty intuitive.  It takes a little effort to learn, as there are a ton of different units and abilities,  but that is part of what you are there for in a game like this, no?At first I was overjoyed.  The AI played pretty well and the game felt challenging but fair.  I could tell I was going to sink a lot of playtime into this game.  Then in the middle of a campaign mission (thats about 4 hours in) the AI starts spamming my cities with something called ""Incite Riot"".  So the way this works is that your cities have a HAPPINESS level that determines how hard they work and fight.  Normally my cities mid-game are in the 50-150 range of happiness.  Incite Riot drops the happiness -600 AND if you don't get rid of it in a few turns the city riots, spawning a bunch of enemy rebel units you need to deal with.The way these GLOBAL spells (that you cast on the strategic map, not the tactical) is that they cost an certain amount of mana and if you generate say 70 mana per turn and the spell costs 90 it will take 2 turns before you can cast it.  So you say ""I want to cast this"" in preparation and then a countdown will tick each turn until it is ready.    And these city/empire affecting spells last until the opponent casts a Disjunct to get rid of it.  So say the AI casts Incite this turn.  The spell integrity is at 100%.  I then cast Disjunct this turn.  The game says ""you have a 50% chance of disjunction"".  The formula seems to be (200 - INTEGRITY) / 2 is the chance to Disjunct.  And if you fail the roll the INTEGRITY is cut by half for your next try.  But meanwhile your opponent can REINFORCE an active spell all the way up to 200.  In that case, your chance to Disjunct would be 200-200 = 0, but it never goes below 5% so you always have some chance of Disjunction.And that is exactly what happens.  The AI spams both Incite Riot on a new city and reinforces the ones it has out to 200%  integrity EVERY turn.  And I can only fire off Disjunct (at a 5% chance) every other turn.  Because happiness is so low my empire production grinds to a halt and my units start getting beaten up in every fight.  Plus the rioting sometimes breaks out.  Basically the game becomes chasing to put out fires that keep getting re-lit until the opponent (who's economy is fine) crushes you.  There doesn't seem to be anything you can do to counter or get out from under this once it starts.  I replayed the level 3 times and the same thing happened each time.  So basically the game is too unbalanced for me to recommend.  Hope my explanation is clear and helpful."
