76561197996166708,Not Recommended,226840,31540218,Posted: 4 May,all,tes4444,"I wanted to like this game.  I've owned and played through the rest of the franchise with great enjoyment.  But this one went off the path...I only played through the tutorial and then put this aside and requested a refund so this is NOT a comprehensive review.  Just what I came up with after playing that bit.A few things I didn't like:Added complexities that don't really enhance the 4x experience.  Example:  flanking in combat.  Yeah, it's realistic and it's a complex touch that adds depth - that I don't want or enjoy.  It's not about 4x any more - it's a combat element that does nothing to enhance my enjoyment of a 4x game.Color scheme.  I'm color blind and occasionally have this issue with games where the developers failed to consult anyone who represents the 7% or so of the population who has this issue:  too many things blend right into the background.  I found this to be particularly troublesome with goblin units.  I could only pick them out with great care.  Imagine playing chess on an all brown cardboard grid with all brown cardboard pieces - your focus is spent concentrating on which piece is where rather than an actual strategy.  Fun is greatly reduced.Viewpoint.  Meh.  What's wrong with the overhead view of teh previous versions.  I found this change to be a detraction from gameplay rather than an enhancement.  It's not 4x without a godlike overhead view of the gameplay.  Tilting that view was a bad move, in my opinion.Customization.  Item creation and such.  This has been rebalanced and is far more even than previous versions.  So even as to be mundane and unexciting.  Game balance is great, except when it detracts from the fun.  Even the item pictures are less fun than previous versions.Overall I didn't feel like this was a 4x experience.  It felt more like a turn based version of HMM.  With a bunch of things that are technically more advanced but less fun than previous games in the franchise."
