76561198064139542,Not Recommended,226840,34272554,Posted: 16 August,all,raspcol21,"Overview:If like me, you're thinking of buying this game based on the mostly positive reviews and high praise, just do yourself a favour and dont! On the face of it, this ticks all my computer game tick boxes, fantasy world, strategy, resource management, empire/character building, all good stuff that i love, but it's soooo bad! It flatters to deceive at first, but once you strip away the window dressing it doesn't tick any box it attempts with any competence at all. So fundementally flawed is this game i have to question the validity of every positive review here. The AI is attrocious, and it cheats hard! A different level to anything i have ever experienced.  It's like playing Monopoly with a spoilt petulant child that has possibly also been drinking vodka who every time they roll the dice and land on one of your hotels, throws the biggest wobbler imaginable and refuses to pay. I have been playing the campaign mode offline.Bad points:1. I'll start with something reasonably simple and mundane, the game's back story (I started the recommended elf campaign). Honestly, can you really not be bothered? It's like looking through a ten year old's school jotter as he tries to write something Tolkien, but different, except it's just utter tripe. It's a good effort for a ten year old, but honestly, for something written by grown ups, it's really poor. It really is the Mills and Boon of RPG type stories. I could do better in a day!2. The voice actor. She really is pants! - It's common on this type of game to be fair, but combined with what we have above in point one, it just really makes a terrible combination. So lacklustre. Ok, i don't expect Brian Blessed, but i do expect something better than this.3. The combat. This is the main issue, so it's going to take a while.Pre battle: - Before battle you can only build stacks of six units, ok, it is what it is. You can gather a maximum of six stacks around an enemy stack, provided there is only one stack to surround. That kind of makes it better. Usually though, you'll build a maximum of four stacks around an enemy stack or two (Provided there is room) and usually you will only do this when attacking a city. For the record cities are ridiculously easy to take. This is bad. They are also ridiculously easy to defend because the AI is an idiot. This is bad. In any battle, if there is no chance of winning so long as you can avoid taking damage for 5 turns, you will avoid defeat, often this is easily acheived. This is bad.  Before starting battle you will be given a rating on what the AI thinks is your likely chance of winning, ranging from definitely getting hammered, to maybe getting hammered, to closely matched and the same going up to highly likely victory. I don't know how the AI works this out but it's usually nonsense on stilts and bar extremes where you get caught isolated with some units you were shifting around, if you're smarter than the average jellyfish, you should win easily or at least inflict heavy losses to mop up a turn or two later. This is all bad. There is an auto-battle option, but this essentially pits the AI against itself, and it assumes you're as big an idiot as it is, and usually it'll banzai your units into oblivion rendering the exercise pointless. This is bad.In battle: - What we have here is a reasonably small hexigrid combat map, i don't like them much, but i can see the logic, so ok, fine. It's very basic. The environments are usually randomly generated, and will take the theme of whatever terrain you are in. The environments are pretty dull.  It will generate obsticles, these are your friend as the AI seems to be completely flumoxed at negotiating these effectively, if you pull them around the map as best you can, flank with units that shoot or are weak to keep out the way to just cause hassle and keep a core of melee units to grind the most powerful enemy units along with support units, generally every single battle will be ridiculously easy! This is bad. The AI can't strategise at all. It also can't work out the best order in which to move it's units and so the more you can distract it and pull it around, the easier it'll be, even if the AI thinks it should hammer you. This is bad. Your units will have a certain strength obviously, and their numbers will visibly diminish when they are hit. However, units will deal the same damage, even when down to one HP, which is ridiculous and kills strategy. The AI will cheat with this, you will do min damage at vital times almost every time if the AI has plans for that unit. That plan is always to flank-strike you, which is all too easy to achieve. If the AI assumes it should be winning, it will cheat harder. %s are fudged for definite, i've tested and retested and it's just ridiculous. There is no dice roll if the AI thinks it should be winning. This makes every battle an absolute grind where the slightest mistake is mecilessly punished. Basically the AI is so poor, that the only way it can be challenging is by fudging the numbers all the time. Critical hit after critical hit when it's in trouble. These are supposed to be based on morale, but in similair favourable conditions, you'll be lucky if it awards you 30% of what it awards itself, and certainly not at critical times. Your leader can cast spells when not on the map, and it abuses this a lot when it thinks it should be winning. Bad. It basically mercilessly abuses every aspect leading to battles that are just a chore, which is a shame as despite it not being the best set up on the whole, there's a lot of potential here with the variations of spells and units.On map: - Exploring the map and finding stuff is actually quite fun (Yay! good point). City development is dull. Resource management is no challenge, just be frugal at first, build sensibly and use support spells, and there is no real resource management challenge. Cities can be taken in one turn by a single unit, regardless of city size. Annoying. The AI cant strategise. It will look for cheap shots, and can see all of your units all of the time. Fact. It'll sit, build, and if it can't just steam roller you will not have a clue and will wait to meet you in a big battle and cheat. The developers knew all this and basically released a lemon because they couldn't be bothered! Everything is lacklustre and let down by the AI. All units are pretty much the same. Leaders have no charchter. Leveling up is dull, both with heroes and units. Diplomacy is pointless, and shallow window dressing that has little effect and even less to enjoy about it. The morale system and how it affects your armies and cities is actually really good, but scant consolation taking the above into account. I'm going to run out of space i think, but i could go on. This is a game with massive potential that is just so fundementally flawed, it's infuriating. Many of these issues, even with the crap AI could have been easily fixed for a better experience, but they clearly couldn't be bothered. It's a lemon, they know it's a lemon (because of how they've fudged the combat), 15 years ago it would have been a lemon. I'm sad i wasted my money on a lemon, i doubt i'll even see it through to the end (Which is unusual for me). Just steer clear and buy something better, there are a myriad of better options young and old! I want to go into much more detail about just how bad this game is and how it could have been easily solved, but when i tried i only got half way through before running out of space. I hope though that you have enough to make a decision. If you read all this and still buy the game, you have less going for you than this game's AI.Peace."
