,Recommended,226840,10310778,"Posted: 1 June, 2014",all,the Unusual Gamer,"Compared to most Age of Wonders fans I'm still reletively new to the series, having only really entered into the series after Shadow Magic - the stand-alone game prior to AoW3. So forgive me in advance if the story of Evermore doesn't come easily to me, but this game is quite a surprising mixture the past and the future with a healthy dash of Civilization.Anyone who's played the first game will remember the heroes and 'leaders' - if you could call them that - and their upgrade selection will be pleased to find it return in this game with a broader upgrade tree and expanded skills and skill sets. Domain also returns from the Wizard's Throne, however it no longer works in the same way as from the last two games. Domain used to be the primary limiting factor in summoning global spells, this is not the case anymore as spell casting has also returned to its original design. If anything Domain acts exactly like the Civilization IV borders, and for the record looks more or less like Civilization V. Domain is essentially the policital borders around which your cities control the adjacent land and - just like Civilization - once certain unguarded structures, in this case, enter your domain they boost outputs in the city it's closest to.The new game also delivers entirely new ideas introduced in this offering such as independant dwellings, which if you squint really hard looks a lot like another Civilization invention - city-states. Civ5 rolled out minor civilisations as single city entities like Singapore, Vatican City and good ol' Sydney town as their own diplomatic players major civs could either partner with or annex as their own. Dwellings in Age of Wonders III are more or less the same deal, city-states and dwellings, or independant cities, send out quests to the major players and offer rewards to anyone who completes them. The major differences are that a number of Civ quests run for an unlimited time or are otherwise a 30 turn race, and the reward is always a boost in Influence making the state more friendly to you, whereas AoW dwellings run more or less the same as the spirit quests from the two AoW2 games - 10 turns, and the rewards vary from a unit or two to outright ownership of the city. The customization of wizards that's build in-game is one of my personal favorite functions, as a person of raw creativity I get all giddy about customization in games, it's why I still play Minecraft. I've personally begun a quest to create Master of Magic and previous Age of Wonders games.The graphics are sublime and the mechanics are well thought out, going for a more traditional angle at fantasy - classes, no separation between the elves. The only problem I have is the game's editor, and again for a creative person like myself that's a big problem. The editor is very unstable; it will work for a while but not long enough to make any real progress on any scenario, even the smallest map size is affected.4 out of 5 stars. It's actually a bit of a cop out, if the editor were up to scratch I'd happily give it a perfect score."
76561198073659380,Recommended,226840,10311847,"Posted: 1 June, 2014",all,BlueDaemon,"Having adored the Age of Wonders series when I was young, I was thrilled to learn that a third one was being made. After purchasing this game, all of my hopes for what it could be were made reality. This is hands down one of my favortie strategy games of all time. If you enjoy pure turn based strategy games and are looking for one in a fantasy setting, I cannot recommend this game enough.In addition to the excellent gameplay, I've been delighted by the constant updates and fixes the devs have rolled out since the game's launch. I often play MMO's and I have commented more than once that this strategy game is getting updated more frequently than many subscription based MMO's I've played.Finally, this game is excellent to play multiplayer as it retains its turn based flavor while allowing your friends to complete their turns at the same time. Even when watching another player's battles you are at least seeing the action rather than staring at a non-responsive strategic map and waiting.All in all, this game is a must buy in my opinion!"
