76561197971425129,Not Recommended,226840,11015177,"Posted: 2 July, 2014",all,TheStratovarian,"I want to like this game. I do. It has a good mix of what made the Heroes of Might and Magic series fun, with a nice bit of civilization tossed in as well. Intermixing a good hex combat system that has many dynamic aspects, but also a good autobattle system as well. It runs well on older and newer machines, with no hiccups, or issues at all. Stable, and dependable, its a solidly written game that doesn't leak at all like a sieve.This is however, where the game falls apart horribly, the AI openly knows everything, and yet is capable of just doing the same aspects to let you walk all over it in the same vein. Where the campaign is meant to teach you how to play, and the proper way to play each class and race, while letting you find what you want to do for when you step into multiplayer. The lack of online games as well truly hurts the nature of good fun times that could be had.It fails horribly. The game does not teach you, and worse,  the campaign is only a massive exercise in wasted time, potential, and most importantly, fun. Losing happens, but getting trounced because the ai can always put the exact perfect counters because it knows what each stack is far ahead of time, not so. And that is just to cite one minor example.This game, it could be great, it could be amazing. It easily has the ability to be. I would hope, and even want it to be.  However, I regret getting this on the steam sale for $20 dollars. Maybe with patches, with adjustments, this game will be, until then, stay away, and if you really wanted your fix in this vein, get Eador: Master of the broken world."
