,Recommended,226840,17177051,"Posted: 22 July, 2015",all,Pineapple Pizza,"Age of Wonders 3 is a turn-based 4X (eXplore, eXpand, eXploit, eXterminate) fantasy strategy game where you found/build cities, level up heroes and send large armies into battle. Think of it as kind of like a cross between the Civilization series (mostly the city-building aspect) and the Heroes of Might and Magic series (combat, clearing out independent units, etc.).There are single-player story campaigns, like in the Heroes of Might and Magic series, though I have not played through most of them. I mostly play sandbox games, typically online with my buddies. Sandbox games are played on randomly generated maps and can be customized for different degrees of land/ocean ratios, amounts of pre-made roads, strength of independent units, etc. In sandbox games, whether single or multiplayer, you get to choose what race and class your main hero (known as your Leader) will be. After that, you are offered randomized heroes from whatever races you have in your empire at the time.For multiplayer games, there are various options. You can play a normal peer-to-peer game with classic or simultaneous turns. There is also play by e-mail style games where you get an e-mail when it's your turn, allow the game to be downloaded from the server to your computer, take your turn, then have it automatically uploaded to the server for the next player.Cities are managed by constructing buildings that have various effects and by letting their population grow, thereby letting the city expand and cover more territory. Territory allows you to include various resource structures on the strategic map for additional resource production.Resource structures can be either guarded by independent units on the strategic map, or be more like a small dungeon where hostile units inside must be defeated. After a successful battle for a resource structure, one is usually awarded gold, mana, hero equipment, research points or, in rare cases, spells.Combat can either be auto-resolved (not recommended unless you have a clear advantage) or manually handled.In manual combat, the battle takes place on a hex-based battlefield similar to that of old Heroes of Might and Magic games, only a lot bigger. The battlefield will also look different, and sometime have different spell effects present, depending on the terrain, resource structures or other things present on the strategic map hex where battle was initiated.The diplomacy system is very basic and is mostly about making peace/war/alliances, gifting resources and such. You can also encounter independent NPC ""cities"" on the map that you can make peace with and even convince them to become your vassals or join your empire.Positives:- Very good turn-based combat.- Large variety of creatures with interesting passive and active abilities.- Highly varied races and classes, each with their respective strengths, weaknesses and playstyles.- Competent city management.- Pretty graphics (units, spell effects, terrain, etc.) on the strategic map.- If you zoom out enough, it fades into a world view which looks like a cool painted map :)- Decent music.- Excellent expansions.Negatives:- In combat, plenty of units use their melee weapons even for ranged attack animations, which looks a bit weird.- Research is not necessarily very interesting, though it is functional.- The vassal system is interesting, but at the time of this writing they seem a bit overpowered and if you get a couple of them early enough, it can really snowball from there, making you (or someone else) too powerful.- The AI is not great. It's provides an ok challenge on King level, but even one step down from that, an experienced player can expand and recruit vassals fast enough that the AI can't keep up.- The built-in reference (called Tome of Wonders) does not necessarily include all the information you might want. This means that something like ~95% of what you can do in the game is pretty easy to learn, but the remaining ~5% is not explained and feels a bit obscure.It's not perfect, but you can have a lot of fun with it, especially if you get a few friends to play with. If you buy it, I would strongly suggest that you buy the expansions, as well, as they add more starting race choices and interesting things like that."
,Recommended,226840,17209003,"Posted: 24 July, 2015",all,Synn,"This is a fantastic turn based fantasy strategy game very much in the spirit of Master of Magic. It doesn't have very deep city building or anything like that, in fact in a lot of ways the game is pretty simple. But the simple aspects of the game combines very well to create a rich and deep experience.You never really feel overwhelmed or bogged down yet you also tend to always feel like you have important decisions to make even in the late game. It's a superb game by a developer that seems commited to supporting it with balance patches and new content down the road."
