,Recommended,226840,31909704,Posted: 22 May,all,Drumpf,"There are some do's and don'ts to fully enjoy this game, in my humble opinion:Do get the expansions, do play random maps, DON'T play with simultaneous turns, do turn on classic turns, do try out all the varieties and combinations of classes and races, do experiment and expect that your first game or three might not go strongly. The game is not terribly complex, it's very easy to pick up and quite intuitive. At first somethings may seem overwhelming, but they'll fall into place quickly. You might find yourself using google a couple times.If you find yourself not enjoying the tutorial or campaigns, don't bother with them. They're not the strategy 4X you're looking for, in my opinion. If you're a fan of Civilization-like 4X games, again, you want to play random maps.That being said, I was hyped when I got this game originally but didn't really enjoy it. Now it's a favorite. I recommend it, especially to anyone who likes the idea of a fantasy or non-""historical"" 4X game."
76561198030916207,Recommended,226840,31563605,Posted: 5 May,all,dmcf,"The basic game and campaign are great. The most similar game to it is the Heroes of Might and Magic series, but Age of Wonders adds lots of features HOMM lacks - and it also takes out the worst flaws in HOMM.There are no stacks of hundreds or thousands the way there are in Heroes of Might and Magic games - just one unit or one hero - and even the lowest level units are always useful. Units also gain stats and even special abilities from gaining experience ranks.It's a combination of adventuring/ clearing out dungeons etc and fighting AI controlled kingdoms, plus roaming monsters and brigands and clearing out theur lairs, gold mines, mana nodes etc. On top of that your existing cities grow, increasing the area they control and get resources from, you can found new settlements, and conquer existing ones, or make alliances with them which can turn into them becoming vassal cities or joining your empire.You really need to think about tactics and strategy and skill choices for heroes.There is a great atmosphere and a big range of unit types, hero and lord types, spells and skills and special abilities. And a good storyline that also gives you choices that affect what missions you get.But even when you're finished with the campaign, it keeps getting better. The two main expansions (Golden Realms and Eternal Lords) add in two new campaigns and four new races - but that's the least of what they add. There are new special locations to clear out - and on top of that these unlock new buildings if they are in the domain of a city you have or that you build there. These can add bonuses or even special abilities to some unit types, add extra  kinds of defences or income to the city, or unlock new unit types for recruitment in that city.Then there are the Empire Quests that , if e.g you are first to have seven cities, you get a bonus to happiness and gold income from them. If you are first to get 100 units then all your heroes and units level up immediately etc.And there is Race Governance Experience - which lets you gain levels in governing that race and choose bonuses to some or all units of that race, or cities of that race.And there are new specializations for lords - Keeper of the Peace (good alignment), Grey Guard (neutral) and Shadowborn (evil)And then there are all the great free mods that you can install if you have the two main expansions which add in new unit types , new buildings, new specializations, better graphics for existing units, new heroes, new skills heroes can choose, buildings that let you recruit new good or evil units, or make all new units recruited in that city dedicated to good or evil, and all kinds of other great thingsThe ultimate spells are a bit over-powered , but there are mini-mods to remove them.The only part of the game that isn't quite as great is multiplayer. The problem here is that if one player fights out a battle manually against neutrals or the AI (the way they would in single player) any other players have to wait and can't do anything until the battle is over. But if you set it to auto-calc only for battles with the AI then you lose lots of units you would not lose if you had fought that battle out.And unless you are part of a Steam Group for multiplayer for the game, or playing people you know in real life, there is a high rate of people just quitting without explanation.That said the single player campaigns and random maps are so good it's worth buying and getting the expansions just for them. And multiplayer versus people you know can be great too.I'd advise against buying the Deluxe version though as this only adds one map scenario - and you effectively get unlimited maps /scenarios between random maps and free maps made as mods in the steam workshop.P.s Don't bother with the package with Age of Wonders I or II either - for me at least they won't even run on Windows 10"
,Recommended,226840,31574248,Posted: 5 May,all,ButtonMash0847,"If you are a fan of fantasy/medieval games that involve growing your own kingdom, making alliances, and battling monsters off of your domains, then this game is PERFECT for you! What makes this game unique from Civilization is the fact that there are ""Independents"" they are random monters, and NPC Cities, these guys really spice up the game, to the point where sometimes enemy players aren't a threat in the beginning, Independents are! I've only had this for a few days and already have 16 hours on record. What I love about this game is that there is NO real rush to it, it's a game that you sit down to, play for a few hours, save, and pick it up the next game. As a noob to the game my average game genuinely lasts about 2-3 days where I play for a minimum of 3 hours a day. And the ENDLESS leaders you can customize makes this all the better, tired of playing Druid Elves that focus on range? You can make a new character that focuses on Humans and mass producing massive armies to crush your oppenents! I got bored of this game for a little bit because I kept losing as elves, but then I realized that there are much more options to choose from and I loved the game all over again. This game lags a bit on a potato computer (Mines a 4 GB Ram with a 2.4 GZ Proccessor and its a little choppy but that's it!) even on the lowest graphic settings it still looks pleasing to the eye, if you've got a higher end computer then on ultra this game looks purely elegant. The combat system is a little hard to master, such as which unit counters another unit and which units do what, and the game is very overwhelming for new players, but after playing for a day you will understand almost aspect of the game.Rating: 9.5/10 (This is the first time I've EVER given a game this rating before, my previous highest was an 8.5)"
76561198023082933,Recommended,226840,31911340,Posted: 22 May,all,toucanbuzz,"The best turn-based fantasy strategy game I've ever played. The story-line is average, but the heroes, magic, graphics, troops, soundtrack, and pretty much everything else rocks. Got the expansion, great addition of two new races and another campaign. The game involves a LOT of combat, so at some point you're going to have to get used to the ""auto"" combat feature (computer usually does a decent job, ""quicksave"" is your friend if you fear you'll get screwed over), and several maps are not for the meek. Hunkering down in your towns is a losing proposition.The game bounces back and forth between your main heroes as they become the focus of a chapter. There's a ""choice"" in each campaign where you make a major decision that branches you off into a different map or two and gain/lose a hero to that choice, giving it some story replayability. Ultimately, the campaign is enough for dozens of hours of challenge, and there will be frustration for new players as certain maps are unforgiving (the archipelago map, for example, will overwhelm you unless you can strike early and decisively on some enemy islands, flying heroes spec'd for physical combat for the win).  Anyways, too much to say without spending pages, so whether this game is on sale or not, a fantastic buy."
